{"product_id": "628800", "page": 1, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-21", "text": "Plays like Gradius , Or Super-C\nPLays like Star -fox ( Branching Paths )\nPlays like it was made in arcades in the late 90's\nplays very nicely. good powerup system ( when I learned how it worked, that is )\nYou unlock a main weapon ( from a large num,ber of shot types )\nYou unlock a sub weapon  ( Liek missles that shoot below you when you fire the main weapon )\nYou unlock special attack weapons, like missles ( limited in number,powerful - but also a waste - more on that in a second)\nThe Powerup system works in two ways : green orbs for your main weapon, red orbs for your sub weapon.\nBut then there are special enemies that drop an icon changing powerup that gives you a special attack weapon ( like a missle,one use ) or a speed booster, or a shield ( shield doesn't stack multiple times, the speed boost is stackable, and you can collect many special attacks)\nYou go from level to level, fighting mid bosses, scroling the vertical expanse ( levels aren't just on one vertical plane, they go several screens up and down on most stages )\nAnd the stages themselves are your choice - just like in Star Fox\nAre there secrets? yes.\nIs it fun? yes\nA very well-made love letter to old-school sidescrolling shmups.\nA bit pricey, but considering how much content there actualy is... the price is pretty cheap.\nStar fox was 2-3 times this price when it came out ^^ and has LESS content.", "hours": 1.0, "compensation": "Product received for free", "user_id": "76561198277984478", "username": "TemmieNeko", "products": 374, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "628800", "page": 1, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-17", "text": "I kept meaning to write a review about this game since it came out, but procrastination got the better of me.\nI originally played the freeware Hydorah several years ago and liked it enough to give the developer, Locomalito, some donation money. When I heard Super Hydorah was being made, I of course jumped on it as soon as it was released.\u00a0\nThe traditional horizontal shooter style reminds me the most of Gradius. Spefically the Gradius IV/Gradius Gaiden era of the series. This also extends to the music, which has that funky jazz fusion/rock vibe. The controls, gameplay mechanics, and power up system is simple enough where you can dive into it immediately. It provides a good challenge but isn't overwhelmingly daunting. It has multiple paths and several hidden secrets to keep you invested in it. I especially like the fact that you can save/load your progress and pickup on where you left off at any time as you traverse through the multiple paths to the end.\u00a0\nOverall, I'm going to echo what was mostly said about this game already and say that it is very well crafted. The dev was obviously mindful of the elements that make a good traditional shooter and was sure to craft that into this game. The Gryzor87 composed soundtrack is great too. \"No Mercy\" in particular I enjoy. For the shooting game fan of any type, this is definitely a must have game.", "hours": 8.8, "user_id": "76561197996549976", "username": "EXMaster", "products": 1106, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "628800", "page": 1, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-08", "text": "This is the sickest traditional shoot-em-up I've ever played.\nSuper Hydorah is oozing with quality. I won't bore you by talking about how great the artwork & music are, just look at the trailer & demo for those. What I would like to mention is how incredibly dialed in the game play is. These guys have mastered the art of making 5-10 projectiles a serious threat, they don't need 5,000 bullets to do that. The game design carefully rewards spatial awareness, reaction time & tactics, over rote memorization and extreme precision. It's difficult, you're gonna die a lot, but the deaths come with minimal frustration. Almost every time I've died, it's provoked a shrug and a \"Alright that was a fair call\" sentiment. I would say this game is both more difficult, and more fair than any of the great classics, gradius 1/2/3, salamander/life force, etc. 2 player mode is great, if you've got someone that will sit on the couch with you for some good old fashioned gradius fun, definitely give it a try.\nThe ship uprade system is overall very good. The weapon choices you have before each level are meaningful decisions. Death only knocks a little bit of power off your primary & secondary weapons, which is a lot nicer than sending you back to the stone age every time you fly into a wall. It's difficult at first to build up many speed & special attack upgrades, but the game is managable even when your ship has lost most of it's power. I've had to resort to killing most bosses on my first play through with a peashooter and no speed upgrades left.\nI've got a couple minor nitpicks, but they're mostly subjective stuff and shouldn't discourage anyone from trying the game out:\n1) I wish there was a little more red & blue color on the ships in 2P mode. When you're flying level, there's only about 5 pixels of identifying color which can make it difficult to tell them apart, especially if your housemate is RUDE and insists on equipping the same weapons as you for each level.\n2) It's a little difficult to experiment with special weapons when you're a beginner. I see the need to decrement your special weapon charge count by one on death, that's a good call. But maybe you could be kind enough to only decrement us down to 1 in stead of all the way to 0. ;)", "hours": 36.7, "user_id": "76561198005746468", "username": "NoRoo", "products": 43, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "628800", "page": 1, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-07", "text": "Gradius, Lifeforce, and R-Type, all memories from my childhood suddenly brought back to life.   \"The SNES game that never was\"  Super Hydorah is the perfect addition to the side scolling non-bullet hell shoot 'em up genre that was so popular in decades past.  I can't praise this game or the developer highly enough.  This game screams quality of the highest order in both graphics, sound, gameplay, art, and animation.  If it was 1990 these devs would have six figure salaries at Konami.\nThis game is almost perfect but if I could make one change it would be limiting the available continues to 3.  Things would feel a bit more nostalgic then. :-)\nP.S.  Dev, please bring more of your games to Steam!", "hours": 8.6, "username": "Fishsticks", "products": 286, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "628800", "page": 1, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-29", "text": "These kinds of games are hard to find these days, and this is a good one.  CO-OP PLAY.  Very similar to Gradius/R-Type.  Lots of fun!", "hours": 8.3, "user_id": "76561197966054658", "username": "Hammer", "products": 191, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "628800", "page": 1, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-28", "text": "If you have enjoyed shoot'em ups on a coin-op arcade machine. BUY IT!\nIt's awesome.\nAnd the music... Oh, the music... Love it.", "hours": 0.1, "user_id": "76561197970777348", "username": "Liberty", "products": 505, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "628800", "page": 1, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-26", "text": "Super Hydorah is a fantastic horizontal shoot 'em up with varied levels and weapons, a killer soundtrack and great graphics. As a fan of games like R-Type and Gradius / Parodius I'm very happy that this game exists and even more that the old freeware version got the \"Super\" treatment. While the game borrows many elements from classic titles, it feels fresh and unique. Unlike most other shooters of this kind, Super Hydorah supports analog controls. At first I wasn't a fan of this, but after a while I got used to it and even with maxed out speed upgrades you can still maneuver precisely. There are also secrets to find in each stage.\nShoot 'em up veterans will have no problems blazing through the game and even a 1CC run is achievable for most players. That's not to say that the game is easy. The levels are challenging, but fair. Checkpoints within levels and a save system after each stage help newcomers. There are unlimited continues, but if you run out of lives you get send back to the start of the level. Some stages are pretty long and new players might have some trouble beating them. But with the right combination of weapons, sub weapons and bombs every stage and boss can be conquered.", "hours": 11.8, "username": "blizzzilla", "products": 254, "early_access": false}
