{"product_id": "718180", "page": 1, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-15", "text": "Avoid/shoot enemies, collect coins and find the key that opens the door. Coins can be used to create a checkpoint or exanged for health\nIt's a game that can provide some challenges in small sections of each map. But the entire room itself is relatively easy to clear.\nAnd thats because the only restriction as to how many times you can create a checkpoint, is the amount of coins you hold. In this case you need very few, and since coins remain even after each level. it will always be enough to save the game, just before facing multiple foes.\nThis took me long to get used to.\nThe problem was everything about it feels slow and restrictive. The roll itself, is incredibly short.\nIt didn't seem useful, until a noticed:\nA - The  invincibility frames are the entire roll animation.\nB - You may run really slowly, but roll jumping can clear large distances.\nIt's a game changer, my main issue with the game from that point on was the shooting mechanics.\nNot only shooting arrows restricts your movement, sometimes it's really hard to reach that perfect high to hit an enemy.\nAnd both possible options bring the game to an halt. Close or far, you're either holding the shoot button or constantly pressing the roll to avoid getting hit youself.\nIt's a solid game. It controls fine, with the exception of the shooting mechanics.\nAnd in terms of graphics and level design, it is what you paid for. Compared to more expensive platformers it is repetitive. With very few enemies. Changes in the level layout rather than introducing more objects, hazards, or platforming.", "hours": 2.6, "username": "UlverHausu", "products": 3192, "found_funny": 5, "early_access": false}
