{"product_id": "718180", "page": 1, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-10", "text": "I'll risk reviewing this game despite not having played it more than a third of what it is. It's unfortunate that these 30 minutes of gameplay were enough to leave me with an opinion.\nCore Mechanics:\n(+) As someone that played it before release, I'll put it out that the game plays better than it used to. The controls are more responsive and it happens less often that I get a false sense of the height of my jump or distance of my landing.\n(-) There is, however, a slight amount of letdown in terms of what can and cannot be done. You can't shoot upwards, you can't shoot downwards. This gimmick would've made some of the challanges easier, surely, since the game has a bit of a fetish for things falling on your head.\n(~) Deaths are annoying. The price for Checkpoints and Life Statues seems arbitrary. There is a great deal of unfairness here which for the platformer-arcade lover may seem inexistentent; not though for those of us without such godly coordonation and keeness for replaying the same level.\nDanger Variety:\n(~) Deaths which feel cheap aplenty. I took some time to watch some videos of youtubers and they all seems to endorse words such as 'rage' and 'hard'. If that's your deal, more power to you.\n(+) There's a decent variety in the death you'll be dealt. For lack of better terms, there's falling goombas, there's running goombas, there's jumping goombas, there's bats that encircle you. Just alike the platformers you're used with, it's not in the individual obstacle the place where the challange lies, but within the crammed corners, spiked edges and (un)fruitful combinations of enemies.\nPromise of Something Bigger:\n(+) There is a sense of something going on here. There are skeletons with messages here and there, as they do. There are spikes and enemies the existence of which seems to be centered solely upon your demise - again, as they do. The game doesn't hide from the fact that it's nothing more than it appears to be - you're a boy, in a very dungeony dungeon, you run from one corner to the other. Maybe there's some aspects I don't know since I haven't reached that far, so take this with a pinch of salt.\n(+) On that side, now, the graphics are nice! They are not innovative by any means, but it's that good old juicy pixelart we all love.\n(-) It's not an atmosphere to enjoy by standing still, however. Somehow, one not to enjoy whilst running either at times - there's the same track, haunting you, reminding you that you're doing the same thing over and over again. At some point it seems like it's laughing at my attempts with its cheeky notes.\n(-) The levels aren't compelling. It's not that they are bad - they are decent. Yet, is decent enough? That depends from person to person, surely, but I fear that I can't let this slide. Decent is good, but decent is not great. There are new mechanics added to the levels in a well paced manner - yet, they are mechanics we've seen a dozen/thousand times before.\nTiny Details:\n(~) It's a fine matter - let me reword it, a sensitive matter. There are details which evoke developer-love, such as the arrows that stuck, the tiny thing following you, so on so forth; But there could've been sooo much more love given. I would've liked the arrows to go slower through the water, or be affected in some way, the grass to be wiggly, the walk animation not to be unsynced with the distance travalled.\nOverall:\nWe can't make a good approximation of whether or not the title is worth without make a comparison to what we regard as 'worth'. Is it worth in terms of the time-spent cost? As not a big fan of the genre, I'll side with a 'noooot really' here. More like, with a 'worth-ish'. Is it worth in terms of the price-tag? On that note, buy it and see for yourself!", "hours": 0.5, "compensation": "Product received for free", "user_id": "76561198045549436", "username": "Stormmer", "products": 38, "early_access": false}
