{"product_id": "628800", "page": 2, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-09-25", "text": "I am not gonna say anything that has been already said. Super Hydorah is a top ten game. Level design, secrets, arms, music, difficulty... All amazing and very well balance.\nI would like to mention the continue system, if you understand the philosophy of the developer and the connection his work has with the arcade world, you will understand this system.\nWhen you lose the game you will have the option to continue, if you decide to continue you will lose different things: some ship upgrades, points, you will go back to the beginning of the stage, and also you will see a different ending if you finish the game.\nThis punishment creates tension on your game play, similar to the one when playing arcade games with real coins. And this is brilliant, the way you play changes dramatically. You feel the rush when you are about to die, you know there is a punishment if you don't perform well enough. If you could continue without consequences like in most of the present games you wouldn't have this feeling.\nLocomalito is an archeologist of the video games art. He studies let's say what video games have existed till a particular year, then he released a game that could fit perfectly on that year, thinking on the technology limitations of that particular time. He mimics, pixel art, sounds, style, game play, etc. You can see some examples of that on his catalogue: a master piece for ZX Spectrum called \" l'Abbaye des Morts \" (it could have been released on 1986), an arcade cabinet called \" Death came from Verminest \" (it could have been released on 1981). Who would take the time in creating such a games and self imposing the visual technical limitations of those specific years? not to mention doing that for free.\nSuper Hydorah is a really good game, but also you will appreciate its full potential if you have a well understanding of the Video games as an art form.\nAnd you can apply all I said here to the music, Gryzor87 has done an amazing job, if you don't believe me just wait till you arrive to the level called Verminest on Super Hydorah.", "hours": 74.9, "user_id": "76561198263037962", "username": "chindasvinto", "products": 6, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "628800", "page": 2, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-09-24", "text": "A super well done retro shoot em up. It clearly takes heavy inspiration from games like Gradius, but while feeling modern and polished.\nIf you have experience with Gradius and liked it, you'll definitely like this. (I personally find it much better and far less frustrating than Gradius.)\nIf you don't have experience with games like Gradius but ya like shmups, this can still very well be quite appealing for you.\nSo, onto some basic things the game has:\nYour GUNS. You have various weapons at your disposal, specifcally: A Main weapon, a secondary weapon (like mines that shoot below you) and a bomb or active weapon that you get charges to use via a certain powerup. Most levels gives a new weapon unlock upon completion to add to what you can choose from. This can lead to some unique loadouts and even some neat synergies.\nPOWERUPS. There aren't many, which is fine for a game like this. There are little green orbs and red orbs you'll come across often. When you max out on either your fire power/fire rate will improve. Then there are the main big \"3\" power ups that you kill special enemies to get. This powerup, when dropped, alternates between a shield, an active weapon use, and speed/mobility upgrade.\nUsually, you want to get a shield if you lack one as it protects you from a hit before dying, and then go for the other two. You can have a total of three active weapon charges and the same goes with the speed upgrades. And when you die you lose some of all your power ups.\nLEVELS. The levels (from what I've done so far) are very well made and even hold some secrets. They all feel fair and I never felt a death wasn't my fault. Every boss is significantly different from the others and the pacing of the game is very nice as is the difficulty curve.\nThere are a lot of levels as well. This is an obvious gud thing. And as it says in the features list, the order of what levels you go through are non-linear! There are some branching paths in the level select screen so you can go through one set of levels or the other. There are also some \"special\" levels which are designed to be extra difficult but also reward a neat item.\nAN OBLIGATORY CONCLUSION.\nThey set out to make a modern Gradius and succeeded in every aspect. It's difficult but fair, and is one of the best shmups ever made I'd say. Heck, I'd say it's easily THE best I've ever played if we're talking horizontal shmups.\nAnd it's worth mentioning that the art style is perfect for capturing the retro look in a crisp, clean way. The soundtrack is also well done and fits perfectly with the game.\nSo yeah, it's good. I reccomend it. I enjoy it. Thumbs up.  Go.", "hours": 5.3, "user_id": "76561198041765678", "username": "Void", "products": 404, "early_access": false}
