{"product_id": "733780", "page": 1, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-14", "text": "Slabo is a maze game. Your only task is to find your way through the maze and to the exit. I got myself close to the exit and basically gave up after trying everything I could think of to continue. Based on what I played, the game seems short and is vaguely creepy.\nOverall, Slabo is a lackluster experience, meaning it shows conceptual and technical merit but wastes its potential in every way. There's a good concept to this game: solve a maze in VR. Easy to implement in theory. I've seen it done in a spectacular fashion before. The visuals are creepy, but the limited lighting is equally as creepy as it is frustrating. Locomotion is limited to moving forward with the trackpad, meaning you have to look in the direction you want to move and cannot strafe or use teleportation. Roomscale is technically supported, but roomscale does not feel necessary at all and is limited to very small spaces inside the maze corridors or cage walls. The ways in which you move are poorly implemented and frustrating to the player. (I had 2 other people play this game and confirm that it is truly frustrating to move in the game.) There's also potential to get motion sickness from the game, though that's really not something I take issue with. What I do, however, take issue with is the inability to press buttons easily. The game doesn't press the buttons I point at and can be, again, very frustrating because of this flaw. It's a visual flaw as much as it's a mechanical flaw. You need to push sequences of numbers to unlock doors, but pressing the right buttons is sometimes seemingly impossible and can mean having to give up on the game even though you managed to figure out the numbers required because you keep pressing 6 instead of 9 for example.", "hours": 0.4, "compensation": "Product received for free", "username": "Syrsly", "products": 1124, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "733780", "page": 1, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-29", "text": "This game looks interesting. The concept is something that I'm interested in but I cannot recommend this game for the simple reason that where you walk is at least in partial attached to where you are looking. On the trackpad you can move forward and backwards. Left and right do a comfort turn instead of strafing. The problem is that if you look in any direction while moving you start moving that way. I was looking all around and when I looked at the (non-existant?) ceiling I was stuck with instant nausea. There doesn't seem to be any option menus or if there are they aren't the normal button presses and aren't documented in the game.\nI might be able to put up with the slow turning instead of strafing but in conjunction with the HMD look direction move thing this game has currently I cannot play it.\nIf the devs remove that function or at least give the end user the option of turning it off I'll check it out again.", "hours": 0.1, "username": "MarikCraven", "products": 296, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "427100", "page": 6, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "text": "In this update, you'll find some graphical bug fixes as well some new Achievements. The rear and side windows of the coaches should now reflect light and draw shadow correctly, the anti-aliasing artefacts of designs on the windows have been fixed by this as well.\nIn the release of this update, you'll also receive the Kochartalviadukt - the currently highest bridge in Germany - which is currently still work in progress and thus not in the Beta of this update.\n:\n:\n:\nCAUTION: This is a BETA Update. Please note that this version can cause technical problems and/or may cause instability of your computer system.\nHit us with your feedback here: http://www.tml-studios.de/forum/thread/1236-beta-update-1-13-12078-feedback-bugs/", "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "427100", "page": 6, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "text": "In this update we have included a\nwith Color Grading and Bloom. There is a new category in the graphics options, with adjustments for Gamma, Color Grading and Bloom.\nWe've invested quite some time on our\nto make them as performant as possible. These new passenger models also come with all new animations, which we want to expand in the future.\nThe\n, between Heilbronn and Nuremberg, has been added, including the Kochertal Valley and new resting areas.\nWe have also changed the look of the street bariers, making them less eye-catching, and we've optimized the\nin all cities to improve traffic flow.\nAdditionally, several graphical issues have been fixed and new achievements added. The windows of all coaches have been updated, which should fix shading, reflections and Anti-Aliasing bugs and artefacts.\nAnd last but not least, thanks to diligent help the\nis now available. Mille grazie!\n--\nThis update is now available through Steam. We would like to say a big thank you to all BETA testers that have helped us test this update for over four weeks!\nLeave your feedback and bug reports here: Update 1.13.12440 - Feedback & Bugs", "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "427100", "page": 6, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "text": "Following the overhaul of our NPCs, we've added\nin this update. You'll find the previous driver and new drivers in the bus selection screen.\nAs part of our ongoing polish of the map and navigation system, we've added highway and state road symbols to the map, as well as coloration for highways in ongoing constructions including a corresponding icon.\nSounds have been added to the menu buttons, and to the ticket control and sales. We've also slightly updated the ticket sale.\nThe update is available for download now via Steam. Big thanks to all that helped testing the beta version of this update and hitting is with feedback.\nHead to this link if you have more feedback and bugs: Update 1.14.12771 - Feedback & Bugs\nYour TML-Studios Team", "early_access": false}
