{"product_id": "718650", "page": 2, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-26", "text": "Updated: 5.9 hours of gameplay:\nTL:WR - Recommended, it's already got a very solid base game in place and has an interesting background and some very fun mechanics. A few clunky aspects, but overall worth it from what I've seen. And o/c, still in Early Access, so bound to improve in quality (and cost) by the time of final release.\nGameplay: 7/10\nAI: 6/10\nUI: 5/10\nUnits: 6/10\nBuildings: 8/10\nGraphics: 9/10\nTutorial: 7/10\nCampaign: N/A as of this review.\nMulitplayer: N/A as of this review.\nOverall: 6.9/10\nThe game is, obviously, incomplete as of this review - it is still in Early Access. Gameplay is slow-paced, but lacks any form of tactical pause beyond the menu which prevents interaction with the game. AI for barbarians and wildlife, collectively referred to as \"hostiles\" is well done so far, they will retreat when losing and will attack on their own as well as defend their own home-base. AI for player units is also pretty good, though it would be nice if we had more ways to control them (a \"hold here\" or \"retreat\" option would be nice). AI for NPC empires is incomplete, they don't attack the player even if the player starts it. They will, however, defend themselves fairly well. It feels like the NPC empires don't have proper use of the game controls, honestly. Hurts playability, but not to a dangerous degree.\nFinite resources per island is a bit of an issue, but one I enjoy because it makes you ration supplies to a degree. Can't just build endlessly or you'll run out of building supplies. This is slightly negated by the ability to create and destroy islands - if you manage to get late enough in-game to run out of natural resources, you can just destroy empty islands and create new ones with limited resources on them. The buildings needed for these resources are all well-designed and overall both functional and attractive to look at. Some of the details could use work, and it would be nice to have more upgrades and larger towers, but overall it makes sense. Could use walls & gates.\nUnits are fairly diverse and well designed, with different abilities, upgrades, and a leveling system. There are also artifacts that they will, I assume, be able to collect later on, but those have not been fully implemented yet (or it's a bug, idk which). Units are divided into 3 classes: Melee, Ranged, and Magic. All units can be mounted on one of the 3 types of flying animal (ravens, eagles, and dragons) which can be gained by conquering their respect nest types and recruiting them. Mounting will happen automatically and cannot be directly decided or controlled by the player.\nBoth Multiplayer and the Campaign are still in the works, but I will update this review again once they have been released and I play them through. Only 2 of the 4 races are active as yet (Humans & Dark Elves) so I can't wait to see what the other races can do.\nOverall, this game is fun and has a unique premise with the moveable floating islands. Needs just a few more features (would be nice to steal islands from people, for example) and an AI upgrade for the NPC empires, but can't really say I regret buying it at this time. Go for it folks!", "hours": 5.9, "user_id": "76561198031481122", "username": "Fishkeeper01", "products": 82, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": true}
