{"product_id": "628800", "page": 3, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-09-21", "text": "I remember playing Hydorah a few years back.  It was a free game made by from what i know just 2 people, the game designer and a musician.  Despite the game being rough around the edges you could see they were really talented at making these kind of games.\nSo i was really excited to play this, and it pretty much lives up to what i had hoped.  Super Hydorah is a horizontally scrolling shoot em up in the tradion of Gradius and many others.  If i had to pick a shmup it's most like it would be Gradius Gaiden.  It has awesome pixel art, with authentic looking sprite rotation and zoom effects that look straight out of a 32bit shmup.  It has fantastic variety in levels, and extremely good music.\nUnusually for a European made Shmup it has properly balanced gameplay and none of the usual mistakes that are associated with Western made shmups seem to be present.\nMy only very slight gripe is the ever so slight judderiness that your ship has when moving vertically, it's only very minor and the problem can be reduced by tinkering with the games aspect ratio.\nSo to sum up if you like these kind of games or just want to appreciate a game made out of love for the genre with great art and music, you should defintley try this.", "hours": 2.5, "user_id": "76561197994775497", "username": "blackswan77", "products": 183, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "628800", "page": 3, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-09-21", "text": "all the qualities of the free version seem to be present with some additions on top.\nthere is just one exception in the \"micro-acceleration\" that was added to the inputs, an option to turn this off either in the menu or in the game's .ini files would be much appreciated.\nthe game's enemies and weapons have been slightly rebalanced from the free version too, you'll find some levels are a little more hectic and that subweapon options like the Scort are not quite as powerful as they used to be making them more balanced with the other loadout options.", "hours": 1.3, "user_id": "76561197970538686", "username": "tfoche", "products": 41, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "628800", "page": 3, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-09-20", "text": "If you like retro-style games or shoot 'em ups in general, this is a must buy. The free original was great, but 2 player co-op, added levels and other improvements make it well worth the price.\nThe old games we remember -- many of them actually kind of suck. That's why Cursed Castle EX and Super Hydorah are so great. They have a nostalgic look to them (the CRT effects are good too) but play better and have more depth than the actual games of old.\nOne thing the old games excelled at was pixel art. They did amazing things with limited resolutions and palettes. Most new \"retro\" games try but fall far short of the quality of the classics. But this game looks fantastic, on the same level as the best arcade and console games of the 80s and 90s.\nI have to add this is PERFECT for an arcade cabinet install. First, it's native resolution appears to be a 320x180. ArcadeVGA supports 321x200 resolution, so it should run in \"exact\" mode (pixel perfect) with neglibible letterboxing on a 4:3 display. Second, it supports two players using one keyboard. Which means you can easily configure controls for both players using an I-PAC type USB keyboard encoding device.", "hours": 0.6, "user_id": "76561198119835591", "username": "mmacarthur", "products": 343, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-12", "text": "Loved this. Worked fairly well on my windows Lenovo headset.\nProblems with grabbing handrails tend to not look real but you get there in the end and I found the whole experience\nreally enjoyable. The vasteness of space and the images of earth are great and loved the astronaut who came to help you.\nFlaws dont ruin what for me was a breathtaking experience.\nLove to see it developed further.", "hours": 1.0, "user_id": "76561197963517852", "username": "spectra7045", "products": 18, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-11", "text": "Definitely check this out if you are interested in realistic space science. Be extra careful though if you suffer from motion sickness. Gameplay length is very short. I finished it in less than 10 minutes. Graphics looked good but not mind-blowingly great. Oculus' free Mission ISS is way better when it comes to length and graphics. Regardless of all that,  I'm still very grateful that BBC made an attempt to make a scientific and educational experience for VR and I hope they will continue to do so in future.", "hours": 0.6, "username": "EvidencePlz", "products": 191, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-11", "text": "I don't know what I can say that others have not.  Worth your time for sure, since it's free.  I had a little vertigo, but I'm not confident I wouldn't have had vertigo in that same situation in real life, astronauts probably get trained for that stuff.  :D  I played it while standing, I think a surreal experience would have been if I had some way of suspending myself while playing.  Maybe I'll try playing it while laying down in my play area.", "hours": 0.4, "username": "Zerdath", "products": 694, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-10", "text": "This was such a cool experience. It's short but so eye opening to the perspective, the importance and the dangers astronaughts experience on the ISS.", "hours": 0.2, "user_id": "76561197967470514", "username": "Raptorsaurus Rex", "products": 41, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-08", "text": "Controls are a bit clunky for Vive but it's worth a run (10 min aprox). I fell on my butt so just that makes me want to recommend it.\nEmptiness of space is well made but earth texture lacks quality. Some relative loved space related stuff and loved it regardless.", "hours": 0.6, "username": "proteiN_as", "products": 129, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-08", "text": "Short but Sweet.", "hours": 0.6, "username": "Bazinga!", "products": 73, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-07", "text": "Though it is a very cool experience, after the first two tries attempting to use the booster efficiently I gave up as I didn't want to replay the beginning over and over again, I've actually reached different parts of the ISS and you die no matter what, which makes it feel less believable than if they put me farther away and made it actually impossible to reach despite all the invisible barriers that try to block you. There should at least be a checkpoint where we can replay the jetpack portion of the experience to get the hang of how it works for people that would like to retry. Also the on-rails control of the hands feels very odd as well.", "hours": 0.5, "user_id": "76561197997969822", "username": "SierraWolf", "products": 32, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-06", "text": "Oh snap! This is instance of what I know to be 'premium VR'. I'm an expert on the matter, you see, and when I use that phrase, you know it's good.\nIt's, I dunno, 10 minutes or so, up on the ISS? Good times. I thought everything was going well, but trying to get back to the ship failed, and I ran out of gas. I failed, and the game didn't let me try again! It went back to the beginning!\nBully!", "hours": 0.2, "username": "byteframe \ud83d\ude17 is causal \ud83e\udd12", "products": 2665, "found_funny": 3, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-06", "text": "Not a very well made game at all. Very cool and not bad for a free game but it would be served better as a short video.\nI'll start with the good.\nThe visuals are pretty fantastic (when you are only looking straight forward. I'll explain later)\nThe feeling of vertigo during a specific scene is very well done and helps put you into the mindset of your character.\nNow for my issues with this game.\nFirst and foremost are the controls or more accurately what passes for controls. Your actual hands and the hands in VR are almost never in the same place and I don't quite understand why there is such a huge disconnect. I wasn't trying to break the game by moving my arms super fast, I was getting into the movement system and moving my arms slowly to really feel like I was in zero G, but even then the in game arms basically stayed totally still and forced you to basically rip your arms back and forth in real life to get them to move even an inch in game. What's worse is the controls just failed within the first 2 minutes of the game when you need to leave a hatch and go outside the ISS. The motions that would make logical sense do nothing so instead you are forced to rip your arms up and down to force the game to do what feels like the opposite of what you should be doing to move in the way it asks you to.\nIt's really quite hard to explain, but it just feels terrible and incredibly inaccurate.\nThe game looks incredible but if you try to look behind you you're greeted with a black void where the back of your helmet should be. Its really quite strange, it seems like they thought nobody would try to look around and just didnt bother to create visuals for behind you. This shatters an otherwise decent sense of immersion (well, at least decent until you try to move).\nThere is a scene where sunset happens and it's done so poorly I cant imagine what they were thinking. They comment the sun is about to set and it just blasts behind the earth like it really needs to take a\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665 Seriously, in about 3 seconds it traveled around 45 degrees of the earth's circumference and vanished never to be seen again. Would it really have been so much work to have the sun just barely visible and watch an actual sunset?\nWhat's also odd is the way the game handles arm models. Usually in VR you only see your hands and maybe a forearm but here your arms seem to just shoot out the sides of your head in a creepy and unnatural way. I tried ducking and moving my arms lower to combat this ear arm effect but nothing seems to work.\nWorst of all the game was so lazily put together they couldn't even make it end in a believable way...\n{{ SPOILERS AHEAD }}\nAt the end of the space walk, you are blasted away from the ISS and float out into space in a wild and uncontrolled way (this is the scene I was refering to earlier), it's done so well and it puts you into a panic because you actually feel like your sense of balance leave you as you spin into the darkness only occasionally seeing the earth. That's all well and good but they tell you to use a jet booster to get back to the ISS. This is actually pretty cool even tho it amounts to nothing but looking forward and pulling the trigger on the controller. The problem comes when you start to get close and the game just decided \"Nope, you've gone too far\" and suddenly you stop moving forward and just say in one place as the jets deplete. You're supposed to die and im fine with that, but why in the world would the jets just stop moving you forward when you clearly had more than enough fuel to make it back to the station? Just start me further back so that feeling of panic sets in as the station becomes bigger and bigger and my fuel gauge begins beeping only to just fail and not have enough fuel. Who thought it was a good idea to put you like 100 feet from the station then halfway just have the player stop moving forward till fuel depletes?\nEven as a free experience I cant recommend this game. Every design choice is more baffling than the previous one, from the creepy arms shooting out the sides of your face, to the terrible translation of controller motion to in game movement, to the sun that literally just falls out of the sky that would logically show back up in around 20 seconds if it continued at that speed, to the literal 45 seconds of being stuck in place to force the end scene. I just cant imagine anyone who worked on this game has even played a video game let alone a VR game before.\nWhat were they thinking?", "hours": 0.2, "username": "HeWhosKnownAsIAm", "products": 457, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 3, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-06", "text": "I associate the BBC with remarkavble productions like Blue Planet, a liitle presumptious I guess and probably why this was a disappointment. Once you're on the arm it works a treat and the sense of 'beng there' is just great, this is what gets it the thumbs up.\nThe reaminder of the experience is poor in comparison to other VR releases, and whilst you are warned as to how green you may feel from the camera movement you arn't really left with an option to avoid it. None the less it's free and so should be something everyone has at least one attempt at.", "hours": 1.2, "user_id": "76561198072350122", "username": "lewnel", "products": 135, "early_access": false}
