{"product_id": "618710", "page": 1, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-01", "text": "A very good turn-based dungeon crawler, that I'd be tempted to call great if it wasn't for the tiny issue that a following game in the series; Elminage Gothic, is imo better.\nEveryone's mileage may vary though and E:O is certainly more forgiving than Gothic. With an auto-map right from the start and less enemies that can instantly kill you in the first few dungeons, this game is a better entry point into the series than Gothic. It can still be a bit obtuse, with little in the way of explanation in-game. Be prepared to look stuff up online, probably from the comprehensive Japanese Wiki, (thank you Google translate!)\nMake a party of 6 characters in the training school, form a party in the bar and then go out and explore dungeons, solve puzzles and bash monsters, all in turn based combat that has suprising depth when you understand it.\nDon't go in expecting AAA graphics, but it looks better than emulating it from PSP and the translation is better. The key thing is that the gameplay is great. You get one save file, although you can save anywhere, and trying to get all the dungeons mapped out can be a tense and exciting affair. Later dungeons have all the staples you'd expect of the genre- anti-magic zones, dark zones, teleporters and more. Manage your spells, HP and items and get back alive from the depths! Levelling comes pretty fast, especially straight away, and the stat increases on levelling seem more generous than in Gothic.\nThere's precious few of these games being made outside of Japan, so English language versions of crawlers of this depth are few and far between. Buy it and see what all of us crawler fans find so enjoyable!", "hours": 36.7, "user_id": "76561197976001598", "username": "Shackleton", "products": 351, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "618710", "page": 1, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-29", "text": "I can recomend it for original Wizardry game fans.\nNew features(PC):\n-PgUp+PgDn+Esc(LB+RB+start) to soft reset.\n-Keyboad configuration tool in Installation folder.\n-Advanced option setting (edit Elminage.ini. ex:AntiAlias=1 to enable anti aliasing).\n-Customise BGM (SOUNDLOAD).", "hours": 5.6, "user_id": "76561198067679075", "username": "CRW", "products": 2151, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "618710", "page": 1, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-29", "text": "Haven't played much yet, but as a big fan of Elminage Gothic I can already see I'm going to love Elminage ORIGINAL.\nA few quick impressions:\nThe translation is better than Gothic's so far, which is great to see (hope they continue to improve in this area for future ports.)\nSome convenience features are really nice for a change of pace from Gothic's brutal dungeon-crawling (mini-map with icons makes navigating the dungeon easier, and using the map isn't tied to a consumable item, so you won't get lost as easily.)\nNot a ton of settings to tweak in the settings menu but it gets the job done. Can configure a lot of small details in the UI, the speed of text in the game and more. I'm playing in 4K, which brings me to my next point.\nLike Elminage Gothic, the artwork and overall aesthetic of the game is gorgeous. For a PSP port that costs less than $10, I'm impressed. The wall tiles and textures are not very high res, but the portraits and character art are really charming and beautiful even if they aren't ultra high res. It's surprising considering the port is coming from a PSP game. (Turn on Supersampling AA x8 and force on every graphical enhancement in the Nvidia Control Panel. It actually makes a difference in how the game looks, even on 4K resolution, and the game will still run great.)\nThe music is also lovely. Has a sort of classic JRPG vibe to it, very atmospheric as well. And there is a feature where you can change the music in-game and put your own music in each location, etc.. Cool! You can do the same for faces and character portraits, too.\nAs for the gameplay, it's classic Elminage. Create a party from a vast array of character choices, dive through deadly, labyrinthine dungeons collecting tons of loot, leveling up, fighting devlishly tricky monsters and groups of monsters while trying to survive and piecing together the story from NPC encounters you find and bits of mystery you pick up along the way. There are many unique pieces of gear to find and use, many different types of monsters to slay, from Giant creatures to Insect creatures and even God creatures. Lots of ways to express your creativity in how you design and outfit your characters from the large amount of races, classes and loot you can equip, and more.\nOne difference from Elminage Gothic is that it's a bit more open. As soon as you finish the first dungeon you are free to go all over the map to many different locations (most of which you'll die at.) You have to collect Fame by doing side quests you'll find in the various towns, which you then use to power your Compass to help find the legendary Rings of the gods and save the world. There is a lot to sink your teeth into here, and the dungeons are large with a good amount of challenge, interesting things to find, secrets and more.\nI'd say if you're like me and a big fan of challenging dungeon-crawlers with turn-based combat, lots of party synergy and character development opportunities, fun exploration, looting, and survival/party management aspects in an RPG, definitely check this one out. And grab Elminage Gothic, too, if you haven't. ORIGINAL seems like a step under Elminage Gothic in challenge, so if you were put off by the somewhat brutal design of EG, this is an easier entry into the series, IMO.\nWill update the review later, possibly. Thanks for reading!\nP.S. Make sure to read the General FAQ and Starting Tips threads on the Steam forum! They are a must. Once you get deeper into the game you will learn it like any good RPG system, but you may also want to keep an eye on the wikipedia or look up information for the ruleset when needed.\nAnd feel free to read my exciting antics in the very first dungeon (essentially the tutorial dungeon.) Was really something!", "hours": 5.6, "username": "Fluent", "products": 263, "early_access": false}
