{"product_id": "512270", "page": 4, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-05", "text": "Have you ever wanted to know what it feels like to be an astronaut? Well now you have your chance with Home - A VR Spacewalk. Aboard the International Space Station, you are tasked with assessing the outside hull for damages due to a recent meteor shower. Without spoiling the details too much, along the way an unexpected accident happens, and you must think quickly to avoid being stranded in the void of space; left to die of suffocation, hypothermia, or both. The title does house two game modes, easy for those who get motion sickness easy, and advanced for people like me who can stand flipping end-over-end out in space for all eternity. Both are similar, though the latter is just more dizzying,\nThis is the first VR game that has ever given me legitimate chills. As you pull yourself up and out of your little dwelling within the ISS, your hair cannot help but stand on end as you gaze up at the beautiful sight of Earth, 250 miles above you. It's not so much about what you're doing in this game, which is reviewing the ISS hull for needed repairs, but all of the possibilities that this short tech demo could bring; Alien VR, Borderlands VR, Red Faction VR? Who knows, but the possibilities are endless. Sure, it's not perfect and the gameplay is a little rough around the edges, but the experience is there and it's the first of its kind on Steam.\nIf you're wanting to get out in to the vacuum of space, then Home - A VR Spacewalk is an excellent experience. Just don't go in with hopes of it being a fully polished miracle, it was made by the BBC after all. That being said, the first time that you pull yourself up and out of the ISS, you'll be whispering a breathless \"wow\" at the amazing scenery around you. It probably could've done without the dark, and somewhat horrifying, twist, but that probably would've led this short experience to be a bit dull. It's one of the most unique free games available, so be sure to check it out.\nThe Virtual Reality Network\n|\nClick for More", "hours": 0.4, "username": "The Horror Network", "products": 2583, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 4, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-04", "text": "As a free to play experience of about 5-10 minutes, it is OK. However the sense of wooaa is really there I felt. it seems there is a disconnect between the speed of rotation of the ISS with earth and the speed at which the sun disapear which is at fault. Controls are not great, hand rotation is taken into account as well as lateral movement along the scripted path, but not arm length variation with your ankor point, which again break the immersion. rotation of the hand does not rotate your body either. All in all a good intro to VR experience, but given such exceptional setting, it is a shame that the execution is not as polished as it should have been... Particularly for a first BBC experience AFAIK...", "hours": 0.5, "user_id": "76561198166959312", "username": "T0ysWAr", "products": 28, "early_access": false}
