{"product_id": "718650", "page": 4, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-09", "text": "I quite like the game and I can see in my minds eye where it is going to go. The only thing I could really fault in this game are two things.\nFirst - The Economy. The game is all about gathering resources gold, wood, food etc. etc. but there are only two ways to generate gold. You either have idle citizens or work a gold mine. Working the gold mine isn't really the greatest option though, as the idle citizens earn almost the same amount of gold if they weren't working. Everything in this game is reliant on gold, and the further away you build your islands, the more upkeep and everything in general costs. You can sell things at the market but generally, you don't get much.\nSecond - Hero units. The Hero units you get in game are not really heros. They are simply soldiers, mages and archers. There are scout's as well, but I don't really count them as a hero. Now you will find yourself in combat fairly early on, nothing difficult but bothersome depending on where your barracks are located as the units just simply have a nice stroll to fight the enemy. If you don't put a gold price on them though, your Heros only attack one at a time. The combat simply could use some work.\nNow apart from those two things above the game is great, but please don't take this the wrong way. The economy and heros are a different system but completely workable. The game play is solid, graphics are very pretty, music is good. Moving islands around and that sort of thing are great as well.\nWhilst I know this is early access, I do recommend this. At this stage, I would rate this a solid 8/10. With further updates, I look forward to see what else comes along.", "hours": 3.0, "user_id": "76561197986131374", "username": "Phalebus", "products": 225, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": true}
{"product_id": "718650", "page": 4, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-09", "text": "Good game.  Will hopefully still improve.   Worth the money.\nThings I would like to see improve:\nMore character - i.e. the heroes are very bland.   They're difficult to tell apart, they have no distinct moves, I haven't found any abilities to give them, etc.\nIts an odd mix of micro and macro management - place and forget for the most part, but would like to improve it by 2 settings - auto demolish (demolish any useless building and clear the detritus), auto build - build a building for any resource.  Once the main resource has been exploited, you may still want to build for the others.\nSomething to do with exploited islands - i.e. once fully exploited, clear or mark differently.  Once you get to 20 or so islands it can be annoying.", "hours": 13.0, "username": "jutetrea", "products": 241, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": true}
{"product_id": "718650", "page": 4, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-07", "text": "Lot of potential here.  No campaign in EA, just a sanbox like mode.  I think the game is great though.  Lots of resources but not to many, intuitive gameplay.  Grab the islands, use them for resources, get stronger, kill your enemy.\nHas a very cool Majesty vibe where you set bounties.  Hereos feel a little bland at the moment, more like units.  You dont really get attached at all.  Still though, its totally playable and enjoyable in its current state and i have high hopes for the future.\nIf you want something thats kinda rts kinda 4x this is worth a try.  Ultimatly its econ mangement, so if games like anno turn you off you might not like this.  Dont get it for the battles, they are there, but its not the main part of the game.", "hours": 7.8, "user_id": "76561198006643348", "username": "conley1126", "products": 117, "early_access": true}
{"product_id": "718650", "page": 4, "page_order": 8, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-07", "text": "First things first: I perfectly well know that this is early access, so I really do hope there will be significant improvements considering unit intelligence, first and foremost. After playing a few hours, it is up to you if you want it right now, or in a few weeks after a patch. The review could also be thumbs up - but I chose thumbs down for now. See unit behavior\nThe economy is slightly (only) odd - achieving even a balanced economy is rather difficult, despite the small tech tree, as well as the quickly to grasp resource system ingame. You need to read/do the tutorial, to avoid applying mechanics of other games that do not work here. So READ or do the tutorial first, or discover your mistakes with low gold income ingame later, as I did.\nGenerating research points is, early acces test or not, rather insanely time and resource consuming, considering the use of research. 100 points for the first economic benefit, -2 building upkeep, needs more than an hour with one sages building. 60+ minutes for the first tech-tree update.... REABALANCE needed.\nThe tutorial is good, but slightly lacking at the explanation that range to castle increases upkeep costs. Furthermore, space limiting farms to often only one per shard, but requiring a manyfold in food per accomodation unit, makes expansion and extension/updates of upkeep intense farms a neccessity.  Getting some stone and wood then either takes a lot of time, since you can barely spare coin to use it on workers, or you need to wager your goods or mana in the market for needed goods. Let alone high level resources such as gemstones.\n(Destroyed a lot of buildings, and rearranged the islands as best as possible. Also learned that updates are a must for a balanced economy, same tier multiple buildings do achieve less considering the upkeep and input.  Also, after almost two hours, islands with resources on had no, and I mean, no access point to place the corresponding building. I discovered this when the first extractors had done their job and removed the deposits.) To sum up, bigger is better, the more high tier buildings and shards the more stable becomes your economy.\n(Game against AI on random/generated map with 2 of 4 mages/races available is the only game option I had - there will be plenty more)\nUnits are nice, a standard variety, massive spells and updates, all nice, BUT:\nsometimes, without any attack commands, one knight after the other goes rampage, on suicide missions to attack alone, while the remaining keep wandering around, then join the fight after all warriors are dead. Enemy levels up. Investing all resources I had, equipped a good party, full updates, tier III , and hey, the same number of enemies, though tier I-II level lower than my soldiers, pop up, and my soldiers and marksmen all die. Then the mage dies, not casting any healing spell at all despite having full mana and the spell... . After that happened for the third time, after one game of almost three hours, I rage-quitted. Units wandered into enemy AI killing zones on their own, dying and dying and dying, wasting all resources I had accumulated, and literally feeding the enemy. Trying to keep the units near my base was useless, and after the first try, I stopped giving them mount updates. Simply too suicidal. REWORK unit AI and rebalance please - greed is good, so they do the highest bounty missions first, but if there is no real quest, they shall not go on suicide runs. Also, considering the mount costs, the utility they provide is by far not worth the effort, and the vastly improved movement options increase suicidal tendencies.\nWhat I noticed was that enemy units worked better than my own, having a far better targeting priority for example. My knights stumbled around, only to attack the tank, while being hit for two minutes by several archers next to them. Bounties didnt change this at all. Finally, attacks on enemy territory are also suicide, because your units fight to death, or glory, and nothing else. Hence the enemy can cast spells on his territory, and you cannot, say goodbye to your max leveled heroes without anything gained.\nMagic is essential, useful, but: you have a fixed radius of casting-possibility. So, you need to build towers to extend. Updating the main building is extremely expensive, that is ok and inteded,\nThanks to Hamsterbryans comment, I realised that again I must have had bad luck that it didnt work in my game when I tried it out.\nSadly, these two flaws make this game, as enjoyable as it was, a bit frustrating and not unplayable at the moment. Let us be honest, if all your highly leveled and best equipped heroes go on suicide quests after you pampered them for hours, it is frustrating. I will update this once patches are done. (1 update)\nOptics:\nOn the graphics side, the game looks very good, altough it took a dedicated mid-to high end gaming pc more than two minutes to start, I think loading or compiling the intro was the issue.\nI had no glitches or bugs with animations so far, and I am sure the attack animations will be improved as well, but those that are are ok to good. Game ran without any fps drops.\nShard mechanic:\nreally innovative, well implemented, I think you can say THAT makes the game the most interesting. Animations, interaction, all looking great and well done.\nInterfact: Really good, intuitive, most information is well displayed.\nUnit rooster overview: nice feature, but you really get frustrated once they all go suicide-hunting\nUnit update buildings and updates:\nnice features, reasonable, really useful and needed, some improvements are somewhat redundant, but this is early access after all.\nThe fortress:\ngood idea, especially the fortify option, but some adjustments are needed because it feels somewhat unimpressive to have a bassive castle\nBuilding updates and general build animations:\nlike in the intro, very smooth and good looking. Seems really poished.\nFun factor (before massive frustration due to suiciders) was really high.\nAs with many games, I suppose there will be massive optimisations for hardware requirements during finalisation.", "hours": 4.8, "user_id": "76561198005409275", "username": "[WTFH] ragnar_greymane", "products": 937, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": true}
