{"product_id": "609150", "page": 1, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-14", "text": "Ah, Star Ocean 4. It has been quite sometime since I have visited this game. Star Ocean 4 is probably my favorite of the Star Ocean games. Having been my first Star Ocean game, I enjoyed this one the most so far. While the game itself is new on steam, I have a save file with well over 350 hours collected on the 360.\nI really like the combat and it's mechanics, especially the blindside mechanic. The game will punish you if you act carelessly. However it becomes eaiser once you found your style of play and character you like the most.\nThe story is good. I enjoyed it for the most part. However there are some bits that could be improved on. For anyone who has yet to play, I shall stop here. You will either like the story, or you will hate it. Although I do recommend finishing the game to get the most of the story and its plot.\nOverall, I recommend this game. It takes some getting used to. it's only $20. If you got the extra cash and are bored, have a go at this game!", "hours": 18.0, "user_id": "76561198322200057", "username": "Rasten", "products": 19, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 1, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-13", "text": "Star Ocean The Last Hope is not a game you play for the story.  The story is bad, really bad.  Everything from the overraching plot to the execution of it's infintile dialog.  SOTLH is a game you play for the gameplay.  Might seem like the obvious thing to focus on when making a game, but a lot of people play rpgs specifically for the plot and can't handle a bad story.  If you are one of those people, stay far away.\nSo starting with the good, and it is good, the gameplay.  The fighting mechanics are fun and fairly unique.  In battle you have free run of the arena with the only limit to your regular attacks being the speed they take to execute, and the enemy attacking you first.  There are no action bars or wait times involved.  A core mechanic being able to charge up a dodge and timing it just right to allow you to sneak behind the enemy and get a free set of critical attacks.  You also have access to a number of special moves and magics that cost mp, but can be chained together to create large combos.  All in all it's engaging and very enjoyable through the entire playthrough, with new technics being interesting enough to want to continue pounding the enemy's force.  While far from reflex heavy those that prefer a more traditional turn based system might not like the level of constant attention every battle requires.  Beyond the battle mechanics themselves the game excells at giving you a real sense of progression as you increase your levels.  Not with the story, gods no, but again with the gameplay.  The special moves go from a simple series of sword swings and charges to giagantic arena covering whirlwinds of death.  All specials, magics, and skills can be leveled up independantly by spending special experience points you earn.  You get to choose one of three tactical paths called BEATs, two of which also level up and give nice bonuses depending on what your play style is.  Your weapons, which change your appearance in battle (some games STILL don't do this), run from a starting weapon of basically an electric saw to a lightsaber.  You don't just find this equipment laying around some dark dungeon either, well you do find some of it, but most of it you build yourself.  I'm not sure why, but for me knowing I crafted and customized the ultimate weapon gives me a greater sense of accomplishment then just picking it out of a chest.  Finally each of your characters have their own set of mostly unique achievments called tropies in the game.  These can be things like attacking first 10 times in a row to doing 200 squats (something that happens automatically when you land from a jumping attack).  Unlocking a certain number of tropies can unlock bonuses, specifically raising your level cap significantly.  All in all SOTLH really shines at making you feel like you start as a nobody and become an all powerful god.  Not because your background def and str score have risen, but because you aquire flashy new skills, weapons, and bonuses that slowely forge you into a godslayer.\nNow for the ugly.  There will be spoilers, but it honestly doesn't matter as this story deserves to be forgotten.  The problems with the plot and story design in general are manyfold, but I won't go into too much detail as I'm bored of writting this already.  So quick example, Earth just achieved FTL travel and you are a crewman on one of 5 of Earths very first FTL capable ships.  Your mission is to scout a planet for colonization, all 5 of Earths only ships...together.  Okay so predictably stuff goes wrong on their very first jump and all but two of the ships are destroyed, one of which is lost, the other being yours.  You then crash on the planet in question.  After some hijinks most of the crews deside to set up a forward base on the planet, and are promoted to captain and given command of the ONLY Earth ship with FTL capability (the other still being lost).  You are then given a grand crew of...two people (?) and told to...well you aren't really told to do anything.  Just sort of go out and have fun.   You are given no real directives beyond the extremely vague mission of scout out new planets to colonize as if this ship which likely took thousands of man hours to build was nothing more than a mere trinket given to friendly visitors.  So the plot is so mind numbingly unlikely it's actively infuriating.  Then the characters start talking and you will start to look for sharp objects with which to puncture your own eardrums.  From one character that constantly explains everything everyone else says as if there is a really inattentive child in the room who needs to be reminded of what just happened every 5 minutes.  Oh, and there is a really inattentive child in the room for most of the game that speaks in a monotone and says \"kay\" after every...single...sentence.   Early plot devices include the same exact sickness on two different planets affecting two different people and the need to find a cure for them.  Chasing down the invaders to an underdeveloped planet you just happened to land on (how is that in your job description?).  And a very short jaunt to a parallel dimension via a spontaneous wormhole that just sucks you up, and then magically spits you out when you are done there.  You get the idea.  The plot is trite, stupid, and boring, and the dialog is painful.\nMaps are decently large for the most part, and direction is rarely a problem.  The game is very linear with only 3 worlds, each with 2 or 3 dungeons.  2 dungeon worlds that can't be revisited, one of which is very small.   One very small world which is just a town and a dungeon, and then the final dungeon.  There are also 2 post game dungeons which are fairly large.  Decent amount of post game content, especially if you are a completionist.\nDespite the horrendous story telling in this game, it mercifully comes with a skip option.  So I would certainly recommend this game to anyone that enjoys RPGs that give them a real sense of progression and becoming a powerhouse as you go.", "hours": 26.1, "user_id": "76561198198916587", "username": "skott2424", "products": 9, "early_access": false}
