{"product_id": "691240", "page": 1, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-30", "text": "\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665 you for expecting me to complete this. Cuck!\nUpdate: I am friends with the developer so my opinions are biased and might be less negative than they should be. Seriously...it's that bad.\nUpdate: So I completed all the secrets and now I am ready to genuinely hate this game. I find myself being entirely underwhelmed. The real spectacle is the amount of work you are expected to do to find secrets rather than the actual secrets themselves. There was only ever one secret that was ever really \"worth it\" to find and that was \"The Sideways.\" The secret level which also happens to be the best level in the game and the only actually fun one with decent platforming.\nSpeaking of the platforming, It's generally floaty and you bounce around awkwardly so any precise platforming you have to do can become frustrating. It's also incredibly lacking in any variety of features. You can walk, jump, and climb and that's basically it. Everything comes down to \"Run at this. Jump on this. Climb up this.\" and it gets incredibly stale before you've even completed the story once.\nNow where the platforming mechanics fail you can expect the level design to hold up the rest of the game and make it somewhat interesting...right?....RIGHT??....WRONG!!! In the \"Dream\" half of the game, the levels are short and painfully linear. It basically comes down to being a walking simulator with the occasionally press of the space or left mouse button. Fpr the \"Nowhere\" town half of the game, you come back 3 times throughout the game to the same level with only minor, linear changes due to the story. The big problem with these levels come to the hidden secrets which are supposedly the big draw of the game and the reason it's priced how it is. With a little bit of ingenuity, the Nowhere town is left WIDE open and you will have 0 idea of where to go and you'll just get lost in what is secret and what is the actual story path. However the extra level is creative, entertaining, and has a clear direction of where to go but doesn't feel too linear.\nA big draw of this game to some seems to be the art. In the town the art can be charming and somewhat pleasing in a stylized way, but is overall plain and has the just the one boring color palette. In later levels the art style of the town is also brought down by rain and fog effects which do more harm than atmoshpheric good. In the dreams the art style, to me at least, is butt-ugly. The colors clash and the lighting effects just don't really work for them. The textures in the whole game are low detail and plain, but in the dreams they strike me as particularly repulsive.\nThe music does the job, I guess, but is overall just uninteresting and doesn't really get a strong reaction out of me either way. The score could have tried and captured the wonder of the dreams and the adventure more, but that may have required the game to also go more interesting places. All the sound effects lack any sense of punch and feel like just place holders.\nSo with all of the gameplay downfalls of the game, all that is left for it is to be a walking simulator with a good story, but for this game that is not the case. The story has a big sense of being up its own\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665the whole way through. It is fairly confusing yet uneventful and predictable by the end.\nAnd just because of how much time it took for me to complete this game I'm going to say how much I hate the secrets one more time........\nI hate the secrets in this game.\nThey are mostly boring and you get nothing but and achievement and sometimes a bit of narrative that no one cares about. The Toon glasses and Sideways are good exceptions but I only found those towards the end of my journey to 100%.\nI am overall annoyed and disappointed with this game. It would have been much better if the story was less predictable and went in a much more acid-trippy direction with the same kind of level design that \"The Sideways\" had. More creative and out-there ideas for level design would have benefitted the game greatly. Better, more, and greater focus on the platforming mechanics combined with creative level design, without all the worthless flab all the secrets bring, would make a good first person platformer in the same vein as Mirror's Edge.\n4/10\ntry again cuck.", "hours": 10.4, "compensation": "Product received for free", "user_id": "76561198140836912", "username": "Marshallangelo", "products": 130, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "691240", "page": 1, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-23", "text": "So, I bought this game without any real expectations and im glad for it. Don't misunderstand, it was worth the money I spent on it but I was expecting a parkour game. It kinda is, but its more like running from point to point to get to story nodes. The parkour and movement it is very...floppy? Floppy is the only word I can think to describe it.\nThe character doesn't have a lot of traction keeping her on the ground, which means sprinting up a ramp will result in broken legs most of the time. There were a few times where I was confused on where to go, but that was more me not taking any hints rather than the games fault.\nThere are multiple endings from what I can tell and a few achievements for finding secrets etc.\nThe story for the game was rather predictable, but the actual writing itself was well done, and made me feel a little sad at the main ending which is quite good for a game that took less than an hour. Some people may be saying \"An hour? I don't want to waste my money on that!\" which is a valid opinion, but I think if they tried to stretch it into 2 or 3 hours it wouldv'e degraded the experience as a whole.\nOverall, while the gameplay isn't the best the story makes up for it, and although it is less than an hour long if it was any longer it would degrade from the experience", "hours": 0.9, "username": "Icarus", "products": 193, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "691240", "page": 1, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-22", "text": "I loved this game, had a lot of fun, has a lot more to see then just the narrative, the game includes a lot of thinking if you really want to get into it and you have to be smart. good luck finding all the endings! I know I will need it.", "hours": 12.8, "compensation": "Product received for free", "username": "nickthekidNL", "products": 59, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "691240", "page": 1, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-22", "text": "You could call this gamne a walking simulator but it's so much more. The game teels a nice little narrative but it makes you think all the way to the end. The Devs want you to explore and avoid the main path ion the story to fidn allll of the little secrets and references they hid in the game. It's such a good way to spend a few hours in a nice relxing manor i can't reccomend this game more for somehting like that. there's a lot of endings to the game so don;t just rush through the story and call it done take your time and immmerse yourself in the experience.\nI'd reccomend this to anyone who wants a nice story to experince with engaging characters , who loves to explore vast maps and find little secrets hidden away, and can really immerse themselves in the moment when playing a game. If you like any of that I really think you'll find this game charming and worth the small amount you payed for it. It really to me was a fantastic experience, and i think it could be for most people if they really let themselves get immersed.", "hours": 1.6, "compensation": "Product received for free", "user_id": "76561198199379051", "username": "Neodogstar", "products": 133, "early_access": false}
