{"product_id": "609150", "page": 2, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-10", "text": "I'm going to do myself a favor and review this early.\n--One REALLY big thing to keep in mind here is that this is 21 dollars. A complete classic style RPG, 21 dollars. Maybe it's just me, but that really doesn't happen anymore. I actually had to remind myself that dlc costs more than games, and that it's sort of rude of me to make a statement like paying less for a full game when I normally wait so I can get dlc too.\nStar ocean is an rpg of sorts, akin to many other rpgs in its execution. Playing through the story gives you the tales of sort of vibe, interesting characters (though somewhat generic), Rpg like combat, (somewhat generic right now, usually it unfolds more later) And a story that feels like someone felt the need to make a Star Trek game. Which is really nice!\n-The presentation is probably the thing I enjoy most about this game. The story is just about as generic as you would expect. But whoever was behind the wheel here seems to have a lot of experience with making the best of bad things. Instead, it seems they made it a point to isolate what makes some of the tales of games great, which is putting you in the middle of these people's lives. Seeing and listening to how each character deals with situations and how they cope with fear is something you don't see very often. On the ship you get to see how a lot of them try to pass the time as well as what they like doing for fun. It is kind of why you can tell some of them are generic, but it is also what makes it more of an interesting experience. Older final fantasy games had this in the background, which is nice, but I like how much more important they made it here. (Again, so far.) I look forward to knowing the characters more, as well as how they behave in certain situations.\n-The Characters so far contain your typical young hero who is given a ton of responsibility he can't handle alone. Your childhood female friend who seems to need to make it a point to insure everyone knows she is a girl. Your typical human like alien friend, who tends to be more human than humans, which really gives off the tales of zesteria vibe. A robot scientist that is comprised of a mechanical body he made on his own, And he is somehow the most human of the bunch, albiet with an old hermit type of disposition... Which I like a lot! And a little girl who is pretty much what you would expect from a child, her personality is likable, but some of the things she does seems painfully influenced from the girl mentioned earlier. It's really a shame.\n-The combat... Ugh. Personally. I hate it. Some moves are clearly better than others. The base attacks are abysmal, and the combo potential is lacking for the most part. And the whole blindside mechanic is pointless because for most moves there is so much lag that if you are attacking, you'll be hit before you can charge \"jump\" enough to be able to use it. That paired with the fact that even if you set ai to freestyle all out, they still can't pull aggro enough to get enemies off your back, the targeting system is just not great either, it says it will target what you are facing... Sometimes you just get blessed with X-Ray vision and run clear past what's in front of you. Furthermore, the skill move system is just flat out bad. You can hold two trees, and those trees can hold up to three moves. each button triggers those moves sequentially every time. You can chain any special you want... most specials cause knockdown which makes only the biggest enemies impossible to hit. WHY WOULD ANYONE WANT TO USE THOSE MOVES?\n-Combat wise... You remember what I said about the presentation? I get what they were trying for. there are skills and augments that make playing it a little more forgiving, as well as a bonus board tree that allows you to use specific combat feats to act as a multiplier for battles you face moving forward. (it resets every time you load into it, so don't touch the game if you want to play in short bursts) There are little modifiers to your basic attack that seem to work if you mess with the stick. Basically, everything that isn't like tales of is pretty great, but what is like tales of feels like a kid writing a paper wrong on purpose so whoever reads it feels like they tried their best not to copy the source by making it painfully filled with holes and imperfections.\n-Crafting is pretty cool, but depending on how adamant you are about finding and opening chests, seems pretty redundant early on. you won't really have materials early on, and more than most times you will find gear better than what your chest makes. All in all, the system is competent, no doubt it will be more fleshed out later as the game will have a hard time being difficult when they hand out money as much as they do.\n-Items seem directly taken from tales of games, but they stack in 20s. every item seems to do this. 20 caps everywhere. I think it's a double edge sword. On one hand, I will give 1000% more concern to item synthesis, because as items near 20 I will get uncomfortable, but the bad part is, you may end up creating weak or unwanted gear by carrying out with that fear. So when a new blueprint gets made, and you just had enough before you made junk... yeah, it'll hurt.\n-Save points seem to be on average about 30-40 minutes apart. Not the worst thing, but by the first boss I was already well versed in cheesing the game if need be. You shouldn't be dying unless you're running out of health or items... And if that's happening... Use the bonus board to fill your needs. Run away to break it, and build a better one. It's really a good system.\nIn the end... it's A fully featured 21 dollar rpg game that gives you everything and you can either figure it out, or use other systems to fill the gap. Story is alright, etc, but moving forward. Getting full games at this price is going to be a thing of the past, Laugh if you want, but I think I'm having more of a nostalgia trip for how much I paid for a full game than playing an old school rpg.", "hours": 12.4, "user_id": "76561198137728235", "username": "Xedhadeaus", "products": 1156, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 2, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-09", "text": "Honestly, I'm not sure why everyone seems to have the game crash on them all of the time.\nIt hasn't crashed once for me. The performance is great. The story is great. The gameplay is great.\nI had this game back on console and never beat it. I repurchased it the SECOND I saw it was on steam so I could play it on twitch and show it to my viewers as something that was part of what I consider my childhood. I am determined to beat the crap out of this game and I will love it every step of the way.\nPS, Reimi is waifu forever and always\n-GDICHELSI", "hours": 38.7, "username": "GodDamnItChelsi", "products": 106, "early_access": false}
