{"product_id": "726160", "page": 1, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-25", "text": "The under is basically a platformer game which pretty much involves only jumping. The idea is to time your jumps to collect all of the shiny thingys and exit each level. Sometimes the level design feels a bit awkward like it wasn't tested enough. Another issue is that the game appears to lack widescreen support. It's 2017, this should definitely have widescreen support.\nI'm assuming this may be available as a mobile game since it's execution is so simple to play and just feels like it was developed for touch gaming rather than a mouse/keyboard game.\n6/10", "hours": 2.5, "username": "Gorkfu", "products": 4636, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 7, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-30", "text": "Home - A VR Spacewalk\nDeveloper: BBC Media Applications Technologies Limited.\nOverall Rating: 7/10\n*Motion Sickness WARNING*\nBreakDown\nType: VR Experience.\nRailroad Severity: Very High.\nInteraction Level: Low.\nSocial: None.\nMultiplayer: None.\nPrice: Free\nPrice Value: 10/10\nGraphics: 6/10\nExperience: 7/10\nReplay Value: 2/10\nDisorientation/Vertigo: 5/10.\nGame Time: Less than 15 minutes.\n*Spoilers*\nReview:\nI'll start off by saying that if you watched the movie Gravity with Sandra Bullock and wanted to know what spinning in space like that felt like, this experience is for you!\nThe experience lets you simulate a short space walk outside the International Space Station. It gives a beautiful view to behold, sadly though the earth is not fully animated so you don't get to see any moving stormfronts or cloud cover but you are treated to a quick sunset. You cannot move around freely and even your line of sight is rather restricted(Forced Camera Perspective). You can however turn your head around far enough to see the back of your helmet. Also you can't actually grab things other than the hand rails. A great little VR showcase that can be perfect for introducing a fellow gamer to VR. However I suggest NOT letting a non-gamer attempt this as a first experience due to the high level of vertigo could easily leave them with motion sickness which in my experience usually leads them thinking ALL VR will leave them feeling that way. The game does offer a mode that reduces the disorientation effect, it wasn't by much. Can't argue with the price though!", "hours": 0.4, "username": "FailingFreedom", "products": 162, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 7, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-30", "text": "Really Cool, with a twist ^^\nThe whole world fells like a suitcase, which you can pull back and forth on the suitcase handle. I feel so small and tiny now.", "hours": 0.4, "user_id": "76561198015224564", "username": "zer0c00l", "products": 153, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 7, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-30", "text": "I was looking forward to this experience but it really fell short of expectations. The forced camera perspective is annoying, and halfway through your visor gets a large, low fidelity \"crack\" texture across it which is very distracting.\nThe visuals are fairly poor, with simple geometry and flat textures, but the experience still doesn't manage to run smoothly. Controls for the \"jetpack\" portion are unintuitive and it's unclear where you're supposed to be heading. Also, propellant seems to run out on a timer rather on the basis of how much thrust you're using which is unrealistic.\nIt's free so I can't complain too much but it really is disappointing. An on-rails experience that doesn't impress visually.", "hours": 0.4, "user_id": "76561197977567069", "username": "Rude Boy Mick", "products": 64, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 7, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-30", "text": "Just tried out this 10-minute experience, first in basic mode (with slower rotational motions), then in astronaut mode.\nA quite different experience from another, just recently released 10-minute ISS experience -\n\n- , I must say, with both of them having their pros and cons.\nSince \"Earthlight: Spacewalk\" is not (yet?) available via Steam, I will rate both of them here for those of you, who are interested.\n- For free\n- More action and more movement\n- Space suit steering with thruster, which you actually have to operate\n- Animated exterior lighting of ISS during nightfall\n- Suboptimal arm animation and movement control\n- Impossible to turn around\n- No explicit in-game reminder as seated experience. And even sitting you might risk motion sickness due to some quick movement animations.\n- Poor texture quality of earth\n- Short duration\n- Good control for turning your orientation\n- Better arm animation\n- Good camera animation. You can even photograph your feet, which you cannot see directly with your space suit, or make a selfie.\n- Very relaxed experience. Due to the slow head movement possibilities, there is virtually no danger for motion sickness.\n- Northern lights and milky way\n- Better earth surface textures, although not really high resolution\n- Possibility to push away from the ISS to drift in space (at least for a short time)\n- Quite expensive, if not on sale\n- Not much action\n- Short duration", "hours": 1.4, "user_id": "76561198046405024", "username": "Captain Slow", "products": 41, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 7, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-30", "text": "I found this to be an unimpressive experience, but at least it was free so for the price it was definitely worth a try.\nThe experience has some physics, in that stuff floats away if you poke it. Unfortunately anything not related to the mission will also float away if you try to grab it, as it it completely ignores you grabbing it and acts if you were punching it instead.\nYou are shown how to move yourself around in zero gravity, but you can only move where and when the experience wants you to. When you are in the \"right\" spot, you no longer move when trying to push or pull yourself away.\nAt some point there is a chance to use thrusters to move around in space, but either the game intends for you to get stuck and die or the game just didn't handle collision very well... as I result I was stuck two meters from where I was instructed to go, had plenty of fuel, but firing my thrusters did nothing and trying to pull myself away, by grabbing hold of the space station did nothing. As a result I was stuck next to the goal line and just had to wait until my fuel ran out and I died.", "hours": 0.2, "username": "Mort", "products": 112, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "512270", "page": 7, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-30", "text": "", "hours": 0.2, "username": "Clororapido", "products": 95, "early_access": false}
