{"product_id": "609150", "page": 3, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-01", "text": "Honestly, I love this game.\nGreat storyline, great combat system, great crafting system. There is a bit of grinding to this game, but that's to be expected of games of this type, so that's not a bad thing.\nBut . . . there seem to be some serious issues which still need to be ironed out for this pc version.\nFirst of all lets talk about the crashes:\nCrashing when crafting\nCrashing when leaving combat\nCrashing when entering combat\nCrashing when transitioning\nCrashing when finishing or skipping movie sequences\nCrashing when trying to load a saved game\nCrashing when trying to save the game\nCrashing when starting up the game\nCrashing when equipping items to characters\nCrashing when leveling up characters skills\nYeah, nearly every aspect of game play can currently cause you to crash in the game. Mind, it might be because I am using win 7 64 bit, but I rather doubt it.\nApparently there is some sound issue and monitor issues which can also cause crashes currently, dispite what they say in their patch, it's apparently still happening.\nApparently there is some issue with denova or some such too, some sort of timer on how long you are allowed to play the game offline before being required to reconnect online to renew your license. This may or may not be an issue for people, I personally don't see the reasoning behind it. If you buy the game then you should be able to play it when ever you please with out having to get permission.\nThere is a lack of configuration options for graphics and sound with in the game itself, hopefully this will be updated in a future patch. Ie, resolutions, etc, etc.\nSome of the badges/trophies don't register during game play. They pop up at the end of combat but don't register in your trophy log. Not sure what's going on there.\nInventory is very limited on space. I can't quite remember if the inventory was this limited on playstation, but on pc your max on most items is about 20, which rather sucks if you plan on doing nay sort of crafting or item hording.\nMerchants are almost always empty of items.\nHonestly, I would reccomend this game, but you all might want to wait until the game developers pull their head out of their\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665and fix all the bugs with this port.", "hours": 11.5, "username": "janarah_caine", "products": 231, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 3, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-30", "text": "I love Tri-Ace -- been playing their games for the past 2 decades, so I gotta say: this should've been marketed better on steam, I didn't even see it on the front page when it came out, I mean what a shame.\n\n-- Saving your game shouldn't take as long as it does, can get frustrating if you're ocd about saving your game data.\n-- Should have more display options tbh (windowed borderess would've been amazing).\n\n-- Camera is a little slow and awkward, just like how I remember it tho. Pretty good nostalgia trip.\n\n-- Story is alright, music is amazing. Gameplay is fun. Characters are voiced way better than most JRPG localizations ( Xenoblade Chronicles 2 :| ).\n\n-- Main menu should have a Quit game option, I shouldn't have to put down my controller, go to my keyboard and ALT-F4.\n\n-- Also if you ALT-Tab in fullscreen mode you're going to have to go into the in-game menus and set your display option back to fullscreen, or you're going to have to play in a horrible windowed mode.\n\n-- I've got a pretty old setup and this game runs really well, props to the team that ported this, even with the lack of graphical options, it's solid.\n--  If you like cheesy Action JRPG's with a fair amount of production value behind it and a solid Space Opera --- I recommend this game. It's a decent one.", "hours": 5.3, "user_id": "76561198074835209", "username": "Rob Lowe's Gay Cousin Frank", "products": 78, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 3, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-30", "text": "The Star Ocean series has always provided a solid scifi themed JRPG and while I think the third installment did a little better, Last Hope is a steady package. A controller is certainly recommended for proper gameplay. It's not out of this world good, but a decent performer and quite a lot of gameplay for the price. There's a decent amount of freedom for a game of this genre but even the basic plot gives you enough to play and ponder if you're into the scifi/fantasy genre. The characters offer a decent variety and enough depth to keep it interesting. And if this isn't enough and you want to go 100%, better have a comfy chair and a few months to spend.\nThe remastering is okay but not really perfect. The original graphics were quite good for PS3 so it wasn't horrible to begin with, but I'm not seeing a huge quality jump in the remaster. Much of it looks actually quite the same, so it seems like only a partial remaster. The visual side doesn't leave you wanting for more but it won't provide any amazement either.\nTo sum up: very good price-quality, a good performer in it's genre. If scifi and JPRG are words that ring your bells, go for it. Otherwise I can only give it a maybe.", "hours": 29.5, "username": "Vekotin", "products": 120, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 3, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-30", "text": "Been waiting for this game to get ported to pc, finally !", "hours": 37.8, "user_id": "76561198073852440", "username": "myone", "products": 5, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 3, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-29", "text": "One of the better JRPG \"remaster\" ports to PC. They've even added in mouse functionality although it's still best to play this game with a controller imo.\nThis is one considered one of the weaker Star Ocean games due to the amount of grind and a lacklustre story but I've really enjoyed what I have seen so far. Combat is on par with other Star Ocean games of long and short attacks with special skills that consumes a certain bar. Story is typical JRPG with a MC and his childhood waifu friend. There's only one main ending but multiple \"side\" character endings that you can unlock if you do the right things in each one's \"PA\". Personal Actions are Star Ocean's version of the Mass Effect talk to everyone on the ship between events thing.\nGreat pick up for any JRPG fan!", "hours": 3.1, "user_id": "76561197981558705", "username": "\u262dEden Code\u262d", "products": 854, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 3, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-28", "text": "Bugs in the game can be fixed easy. Patched now i think. I have played over 400 hrs. Not a single problem after setting it at 60hz in 2160p (4k). The game is not the best of the saga, but still is pretty awesome. I played in xbox360, couldn\u00b4t beat the post game cause the well known wandering dungeon bug, which doesn't exist here. I played the last 150hrs in the wandering dungeon so i'm pretty sure.\nConclusion:\nIf you haven\u00b4t played it, it's a very good JRPG and the port is pretty good, i failed to find something bad with it.\nIf you played it in console, the 4k experience worth it, even in 1080p it looks way better. Not to mention you can beat the wandering dungeon without worrying the game freezes at a random point.", "hours": 286.1, "username": "max784020", "products": 52, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "637100", "page": 3, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "username": "Red", "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 3, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-27", "text": "Couldn't play it because of some fullscreen glitch was keeping my controller from working without effecting the Steam Menu in the background and on my Steam Link. I also can't exit the game within the game menu, have to use taskman or switch to windowed. If developer fixes these issue I will buy the game, but know I asking for my money back.", "hours": 0.2, "user_id": "76561198066570004", "username": "Winter Soldier #3", "products": 343, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 3, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-26", "text": "I'm a little torn on this because I really enjoyed it back in the day. I'm going with a tentative \"yes\" because this game can indeed scratch a JRPG itch, but it's not without caveats.\nPROS:\n* Has JRPG down in spades, with lots of skills, the blindside mechanic, and the general feel of combat and open world. Largely button mashy to begin with but it gets tougher, especially if you decide to ignore a lot of the encounters.\n* Interesting story. Not the best, but it's cool. Ties in an interesting \"what if\" scenario for our own Earth that had more potential to delve into than they gave it, but a B for the effort.\n* This might sound odd, but I've always found Star Ocean's sound and music direction satisfying, right down to the little clicks in the UI. That last bit might be nostalgia talking.\n* A good port. I've had no issues.\nCONS:\n* Boring, one-sided characters, some of which are so bland, the comic-relief characters (i.e. anime tropes) feel forced in there. Every time Lymle says \"kay?\" I want to snap her neck. Cat girl is hungry all the time, we get it. Edge is CRAWLING IN MY SKIN. Raymie has no personality.\n* Very, very poor quest direction, sometimes almost none at all. It's like the game wants to make it a point for you to look through every nook and cranny of its dry, boring world. Which is also to say, there are side-quests from random NPCs and items that you may miss out on, with no indication that they had something for you to do other than your standard \"I'm an NPC and I say this!\" thing. No map indicators or arrows for quest direction, nothin'. Frustrating, to say the least.\n* Can't pause cutscenes. This wouldn't be an issue of they weren't so damned long. You can skip them, sure, but coupled with the poor quest direction, you might miss something if you skip it. (I should add though that if you skip a lengthy scene, you're treated with a brief synopsis immediately afterward. You can also look at the journal for some direction, but it often just leads to more questions.)\nLong story short: worth it on sale. To me, this is one of the weakest entries in the Star Ocean series, but my heart forever belongs to SO2: The Second Story. Still, worth scratching the JRPG itch if you have it.", "hours": 76.8, "user_id": "76561198214592032", "username": "phillipshead", "products": 173, "early_access": false}
