{"product_id": "734580", "page": 8, "page_order": 4, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-01", "text": "BattleRush is a neat little WWII-themed FPS, often likened to a first-person version of Foxhole. It involves platoon-level combat between players who work together to destroy the enemy's base while simultaneously gathering resources to build vehicles, fortifications and emplacements. However, this game is still in very, very early development and suffers from a multitude of issues- but once they are overlooked, BattleRush shines as a pretty decent multiplayer FPS filled with potential.\n-Decent gameplay, controls are easy enough and the actual firefights, when they happen, can get quite intense.\n-Mostly destructible environment, buildings will fall down, trees will topple.\n-A large variety of vehicles and structures to build.\n-A massive and very pretty map allowing for very unpredictable (and audacious) manoeuvres.\n-Poor optimization, but option menu gives you only three graphics settings (low, medium & high) that just change the vegetation as far as I can tell\n-Confusing and unnecessarily flashy UI written in broken English, looks like it was made for a mobile game (should be solved in future)\n-Lack of variety, (gamemodes, sides etc.) but again, this should be solved in the future\n-Several powerful classes (machinegunner and bazooka dude among others) are purchasable DLCs, adding an unfortunate P2W aspect to the game.\n-Strange realism choices (map is realistic, but the soldier models look super-cartoony, grenades are laughably ineffective, no optics etc.)\nHowever, given how early in development this game is, these issues should hopefully be sorted out soon.\nSomething important to note about BattleRush is that the huge map makes games super slow-paced, much like a simulator (only a lot less realistic and tactical). If you want to charge into enemy lines proudly shouting 'URRAAAAA' with guns blazing while a bass boosted version of the Soviet National Anthem plays in the background, this game might not be the best choice for you. Otherwise, if you're a WWII enthusiast, an FPS fan or just looking for something free to pick up and play through the weekend, BattleRush might do just the trick!", "hours": 8.7, "username": "clueless idiot", "products": 7, "early_access": true}
{"product_id": "734580", "page": 8, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-01", "text": "Wow, this game.. It was an idear of my friend AvixHyuuga to play this game on an early morning. Best idea of 2017 it seems! A game that wasn't as gimpy as Heroes and Generals, but rewarded the skill just as much -- to an extent. I'll lay down some pros and cons.\nPros:\n- The F2P classes are still just as good, and even preferable in some cases!\n- Requires team coordination. Playing with friends is beneficial.\n- The Scout Cars are a meme. @AvixHyuuga\nCons:\n- Moderators need to practice what they preach. Telling kids to \"shut up\" does not solve problems, it only creates more.\n- Comms channels are dead or filled with non-English speaking insults (you know the ones...).\n- There's no dedicated in-game voice channel for the teams.\n- There's no balance with class choice, so most teams end up being AT Infantry only.\n- Glitches and bugs still exist, which are exploited quite often by players that know them.\n- Some of the P2P classes are somewhat overperforming, especially the Special Forces and Elite AT Infantry classes.\n- There's not enough people playing the game to populate the servers!\nAll in all, this game suffers from most EA shooter problems, and sadly the same community issues, but is still fun to play with if you just play with your mates. Can't say the same about anyone above player-level on the heirachy though. The dev should review their moderation team and get some experienced moderators on their side before the community hangs up their coats on them.", "hours": 47.9, "username": "[RKNi] Dustii.Logistics", "products": 61, "found_funny": 3, "early_access": true}
{"product_id": "734580", "page": 8, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-31", "text": "This game is really fun. Not only does it look good for a low poly sorta game, it performs really well for the amount of players in a match. Playing this game, I get a foxhole type of feeling. That's probasbly because this game is very similar just in first person, and in my opinion more fun. My only gripe right now, is that you can't customize your controls for keyboard and mouse, but it does have controller support which is good. I highly recommended this game and believe it has a lot of potential!", "hours": 1.1, "user_id": "76561198180493246", "username": "OGTrey", "products": 10, "early_access": true}
{"product_id": "734580", "page": 8, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-31", "text": "It's been some time since steam's been littered in garbage. Here lies another example of a steaming piece of sh\u00edt that's far from being finished, let alone playable, yet already reeking of Pay2Win.\nBasically after no introduction or at least an option to bind keys to your liking you're thrown on a battlefield to... I dunno, supposedly win a battle, I guess. It's not easy tho, cuz' unless you paid, your equipment is close to useless, because while everyone else has submachineguns, sniper rifles and RPG's, you run around with a d\u00ecck in your hand that's doubling as a \u0441ra\u0440\u0440y bolt action rifle. When it comes to shooting mechanics, it's simply one of the weirdest I've seen, and I've been playing shooters for ~20 years. It's often easier to hit a target 100m away from you than someone standing right infront. It also seems that damage dealt is calculated from current air humidity, cosmic noise and global birthrate. One time you one-shoot people at insane range, the other time you headshot a guy three times in a row, then he turns around and does you 115 damage with a frickin' pistol. Bullets have no dropoff or aim deviation and there's a sort of an aim helper that makes it possible to shoot three-pixel large targets - and that's what everybody's doing.\nGraphics is bad. Don't get me wrong, there are games stilized to look in a particular way, but it's not the case here - all the textures are dark, obscure, blurred and indistinct to a point where it's really hard to tell a friend from foe. Sometimes it's even hard to tell what the hell you're looking at. At greater quality settings there's also a shader covering the whole screen which makes everything look even darker and blurry. Tracer bullets, give off a faint light of the same radius, no matter the distance or angle, making them nothing more than a useless, annoying distraction. Sound is equally awful. Most guns even from different factions have the same sound, therefore it makes it even harder to distinguish friends from foes, cuz' you can't even tell who is shooting at who.\nEvery construction on the battlefield can be destroyed, which is actually nice. There are also building features, tho you need to have materials, which you can get from... cutting down trees and digging stone and minerals? Really? I mean I know the resources need to come from somewhere but who in their right mind has time to cut trees or mine stone when there's a war going around and bullets are flying above your head? Inside buildings all sorts of loot can be found like building materials, guns or food. Most of those things are useless anyway, as building materials come in small quantities, so you'll still need to cut trees or dig in the middle of a warzone; guns (often sh\u00edtty) have very little ammo, so there's no point in using them, unless you picked up and dragged along a proper ammo case from elsewhere; and food - it restores health, but since 90% of the time you'll die from a single shot, you propably won't have an occasion to use it.\nOverall during the battle noone seems to know what the f\u03c5\u03f2k is going on, nor what should they do. There are barely any objective pointers or indicators of what is happening. People are doing completely random stuff - some throw grenades on themselves, some think it's Minecraft and build random structures, some camp in bushes killin' everyone and their grandmother, and some just drive around aimlessly with some kind of hard-to-tell-vehicle. The game's either a clusterf\u03c5\u03f2k, where you spawn just to die a few seconds later, or a walking simulator, where you spend five f\u03c5\u03f2king minutes to get on foot from point A to B while dragging a backpack full of needless sh\u00edt, just to get shot from nowhere, die and start over again.\nI know the game's alpha-quality. What bugs me, however, is why developers are so insolent in putting in paid content while still waving the ALPHA flag as if nothing's wrong. Right now the game needs a\nof work to be even playable, because let's face it, in its current, half-broken state it's just a sore experience and an irritating waste of time. There are missing basic features like keyboard binding settings, graphic settings or even some true form of a tutorial, cuz' just linking to a forum post or whatever counts in best case as sloppy half-a\u0455\u0455ery.", "hours": 1.9, "user_id": "76561198021684346", "username": "Junne", "products": 64, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": true}
