{"product_id": "739690", "page": 1, "page_order": 1, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-27", "text": "Now Man Flies! Isn\u2019t that a surpise? Well, no since by \u201cnow\u201d, you could debate that the first flight of an object heavier than air and still capable of lifting a human being, either occurred during Antiquity in Asia (giant kites) or 18th century France (the Montgolfi\u00e8re hot air balloon). For all his brilliance, Leonardo\u2019s 15th century aerial screw \u201chelicopter\u201d was never a feasible design. Back to our game for now. It\u2019s a casual 2D title which has entertained me enough to overlook its flaws. The second Steam project for developer Epic Fire and the publishing debut for DNB Media.\nI can\u2019t really say much for the story since not even a title screen is present, once you boot up the game. From what I could notice however, the \u201cprotagonist\u201d can be regarded as a collective character in the form of a space ship which surely needs a crew in order to be maneuvered the way it is. Initially a red rocket which can be switched into a blue one, after 100 planets have been reached. The antagonists are also the obstacles between failure and success in Now Man Flies. Both homing missiles and static satellites will get in the way or even hinder your space exploration efforts.\nEven if it might be another Unity-powered title, Now Man Flies fails to mention this and the biggest sin it has commited in my opinion, is the limited Steam Overlay support that it features. Sure, the frame rate counter is present and unsurpringly, it never drops below 60fps even on my native 4K resolution. At least it has Vsync enabled and thus, spares me of having to play at a thousand frames per second. Yes, the graphics aren\u2019t much to look at yet it didn\u2019t bother me one bit. Casual genre is never synonymous with \u201ceye candy\u201d. It\u2019s priced accordingly afterall. Well, in most cases anyway. Now Man Flies won\u2019t allow me to take any screenshots of it through the Overlay and I really can\u2019t understand why some Steam titles still obstruct an innocent feature that can promote the game in question.\nThe soundtrack is comprised of just two songs which reminded me of mall elevators. Not repetitive enough to become annoying yet still nothing special. To make matters worse, one song gets unlocked after you pass the aforementioned planet threshold. No voice acting or sound effects are present.\nWithout any story to begin with, you\u2019d be right in the assessment of the gameplay. It has to compensate the lack of a narrative and in the case of most casual games, that is not an issue. Now Man Flies is not an exception from the rule per se, yet it does become rather repetitive within half an hour, provided you can tolerate its gameplay mechanics for that long. No change of scenery, foes and even controllable ship until you\u2019ve discovered a set number of planets. You might say that the incentive to keep playing is exactly the promise of that new song, ship skin and increased challenge through the unlockable Survival Mode. Reaching it, is only part of the challenge. Now Man Flies has an open-ended structure which means that you can keep on playing for as much as you\u2019d like. And you\u2019ll have to play A LOT until you finally unlock the Steam Achievement for over 32 hours of playtime. To put things into perspective, I\u2019ve seen all that this game has to offer, without even reaching 2 hours of playtime. Good luck dodging the same looking obstacles for another 30!\nYou\u2019ll have to endure and even grind through the Classic Mode which has the red rocket travel from planet to planet, all the way to the 100th discovery before the blue vessel takes over. While not a planet for certain, the encounter which makes this transition and marks the culmination of the \u201ccampaign\u201d, is a location that resembles the Death Star from Star Wars. What I couldn\u2019t explain was how can so many satellites interfere with space exploration, especially since we\u2019re being led to believe that we\u2019re breaking new grounds with each subsequent discovery. Also, why and who would try to stop these space pioneers through the use of so many guided missiles? If the answer you\u2019re imagining is \u201caliens\u201d, no other ships or structures are ever encountered. Just the red/blue rocket you\u2019re steering and the far-too-similar-looking blue satellites along with grey projectiles that seem to follow players at an obviously greater velocity than their target.\nMonotony is never setting in, simply because you have to become creative, by the time you\u2019ve passed your 50th discovered planet. Beyond the sheer number of obstacles, the randomly generated levels ensure that even if you fail a certain stage repeatedly, you\u2019ll still have to ambition yourself to overcome your mistakes, without having to replay in the same conditions over and over again. Also, the booster mechanic helps plow through foes and reach your destination sooner It can be used as a \u201cI win\u201d button on lower levels. By the time I reached stage 100 though, the booster was only a minor assistance, as instantly covering 10 thousand out of 30 thousand kilometres (only the Metric system is featured in-game) still gave me 20 thousand \u201creasons\u201d to remain focused on the digital onslaught ahead. Indeed, it was challenging and for this reason alone, I reconsidered my initial intention of slamming this game through a much lower rating.\nIt\u2019s not going to impress you and it certainly won\u2019t keep you as entertained as an excellent RPG or RTS, yet casual games have their very own niche on PCs. We\u2019re not talking of the lazy cash grabs that are prevalent to smartphone \u201cgaming\u201d. Steam needs to host casuals and fortunately, even Now Man Flies is priced within good measure and reason, in perfect balance with its offerings. You get what you pay for, yet it\u2019s still up to you to appreciate the game\u2019s fun factor. Just don\u2019t judge it for its first few levels. If you\u2019re an Achievement collector, it goes without saying that you\u2019ll enjoy this game thoroughly. At the time of this writing, there are five thousand Steam Achievements, waiting to be unlocked within Now Man Flies. With my limited playtime or not, I still managed to gain over three thousand. A considerable number, perhaps even crazy, since I haven\u2019t collected that many in all the Steam games I played in the past combined.\n+ Steam Achievements.\n+ Adequate scaling of the difficulty factor.\n+ Decently priced title offering exactly what it advertises.\n- No Steam Trading Cards nor Overlay screenshot support.\n- Inherently repetitive gameplay.\n- Limited sound selection.", "hours": 1.4, "compensation": "Product received for free", "username": "UN0W3N", "products": 5143, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
