{"page_order": 13, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-12", "text": "At first glance, this game seems to be shamelessly ripping off MtG.\nIt's not.\nSure, it has a very similar resource system, and it has the same mulligan system, and it has the same deck size. Unlike any MtG video game, though, Hex is able to exercise the freedoms that only digital CCGs can exercise. For example, buffs/debuffs on Troops stay around even once they're killed, which creates interesting possibilities for buff-themed decks. Tracking such buffs/debuffs in real life would be a nightmare, especially after you've buffed a whole slew of Troops. Another great example is the socketing system, which lets you add special effects to certain cards.\nBut the real reason this game is awesome is because it has a full PvE campaign. The devs have created so much variety that it has never felt stale. There's always some new twist; in one dungeon, there were these\nthat threatened to sweep away swaths of my deck. If I didn't kill them fast enough, part of my deck would be removed for the rest dungeon run. In another dungeon, there's this branching path and you have to choose between which of two bosses you want to slay. The boss you skip isn't content to just sit around, however; he comes back\n.\nFurthermore, the devs aren't afraid to challenge you. There are several encounters that are simply too strong for certain deck strategies. It's these times that I have to stop and look at my collection and see what I have which can counter the given enemy. There are many times I realize that I simply don't have the ability to handle the situation, though. It feels great coming back and thrashing these encounters once I do have the correct tools.\nI haven't even mentioned how much customization there is for campaign character(s). Not only is there a skill tree, there's also a bunch of equipment built specifically for PvE. I'll let you explore this for yourself, but I'll say that it works surprisingly well when combined with deck building.\nUnfortunately, the PvP scene is not easy to get into. Unlike most virtual CCGs, a lot of the better PvP cards are costly, usually only available for trade using the premium currency, Platinum. Unless you spend some cash, obtaining these cards requires a lot of grinding.\nBeyond regular constructed, there's also a sealed format. Similar to real-life sealed tournaments, you open card packs and use these packs to construct a deck. As you progress through the tournament, you get to open more packs, and these new cards can be added to your deck to improve it. The best part is that you keep all the cards you open this way, so it's a great way for a new player to get their PvP collection started. The only problem is that, in order to enter, you have to use a sizeable chunk of Platinum.\n(Funny story: I was only able to enter because a kind soul pitied me after thrashing me in constructed. Despite turning down their kind offer, they insisted on giving me the necessary Platinum to enter the Evo Sealed tournament. I don't think this happens too often.)\nOverall, the cost isn't too bad if you compare it to printed TCGs; you aren't getting physical cards, but, as I previously mentioned, you get to play a game optimized for the digital gameplay. It does seem harsh when compared to most modern online CCGs, however.\nThe deck-building feels clunky most of the time. (I shouldn't have to click 48 times to add all the resources to my deck!) Also, somebody forgot to create the \"New deck\" button when managing campaign decks, which means I need to click at least 120 times to totally empty my deck and start from scratch. The auction house interface is okay, but for some reason it prioritizes Platinum offers over Gold offers unless you apply the right filters. There are some card interactions that are ambiguous, and the only way to check what happens is to actually put a deck together and experiment. (Not to mention that some of the cards have so much text on them that there is a\nin their text box. As a game designer, this churns my stomach.)\nFortunately these are mostly interface flaws, and they shouldn't be too hard to patch. If you're reading this in the future, the devs may have fixed these issues.\nBut enough negativity. All in all, Hex's campaign is glorious, and I think even players who don't typically play card games will enjoy it. Playing Sealed has been a blast, and I'm excited to try PvP once I grow my collection big enough. I think this game is certainly worth playing, but be wary that it the game eats surprisingly large amounts of time even if you're just playing PvE.", "hours": 90.8, "username": "AutoFireII", "products": 79, "found_funny": 1, "early_access": false}
