{"product_id": "378860", "page": 5, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-06", "text": "Where do I start, too many pros, and some very annoying cons. As a driving enthusiast that goes to the track once every couple months, I will tell you right now, get this game because they have nailed the performance, sound, feel, and design of the real vehicles. The force feedback and physics are downright spot on. I do have to admit you do need a minimum $300 wheel setup to feel these aspects. But I tried with an older budget wheel I had, and its still great.\nPros:\n- The most realistic graphics out there for sim racer. (Notice I said realistic, not best).\n- Awesome physics (Except in Multiplayer, see Cons).\n- Great Driver License system for the clean drivers out there.\n- Online mode gets really intense in a very good way.\n- Detailed design of every single livery you choose.\n- Much improvements over PC1.\n- Magnificent optimization by the devs. Get solid 60fps on ultra, With 30 other cars on screen.\n- Realisitc penalty system (but see cons also).\nCons:\n- Buggy penalty system. Other drivers may hit you, and both of you will get the penalty. Needs improvment for sure.\n- Buggy sync issues when the race is starting online mode.\n- Buggy country flag and name display in online mode. Sometimes your flag and name change position with others.\n- Buggy and laggy servers throw off your drive online.\n- Horrible CRASH Physics when playing online. You may tap a car and the vehicle goes flying in the air. Needs patched.\n- And the only non online con is that the AI is very boring. No emotion, no aggression, just plain.\n- Game crashed and froze on me 2 times in my first 60 hours of gameplay. Only in the menu.\nBy all means, if you are into Need for Speed and Drive Club (Arcade) type of racers, you may want to pass this game because of its realistic features. For those of you in the reviews who complain that the vehicles feel like they are moving in slow motion, its because either you never been to a track, or you are used to doing 220mph on city streets in other arcade style car games.\nI would Also like to see better physical damages on the vehicle, like actually totaling a car by doing 100mph into a wall, instead of the bumper and hood getting dents. I know this is not BeamNG, but how awesome would it be to see BeamNG crash physics in here. Maybe in PC3? Hopefully.\nOne last side note, I am somewhat related to J.C Agajanian, and I was shocked to see the Agajanian Brand 1963 Watson Roadster to be in the game. How awesome was this. His heritage is almost forgotten, and it really shows the depth these devs at SMS went through to bring these historic vehicles to us also. +100 cookie points for the devs.\nOverall - 9/10 will skid and pray my car stops in time before a corner.", "hours": 84.9, "username": "Vano of Velen", "products": 22, "early_access": false}
