{"product_id": "378860", "page": 6, "page_order": 5, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-06", "text": "Honestly, this game is really really close to being good. The racing itself is just fine, however it suffers from all the stuff other online games suffer from, idiots.\nWhere the game is ruined is all of the bugs everywhere. Example, you have worked 4 hours on a setup, and if you didnt save every change individually as a new setup, it may all be lost. Sometimes you join a server and nothing ever happends. The penalty system is also a joke, and is also inconsistent. Some places you can go far outside the white line, other times you cant even go 1 cm outside of it.\nThe AI is also dreadfully bad, its overly quick during qualy, but is super slow during the race.\nIf you want a sim, buy another one than this. This is not worth it.", "hours": 139.5, "user_id": "76561198040137894", "username": "[Nr.2] Maj. Bonki [AOD]", "products": 157, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "378860", "page": 6, "page_order": 6, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-06", "text": "I own most racing games for the PC.  Overall, I think this is a pretty good game.  The worst bugs are the AI, and the setup saving.  The setup saving should be an easy fix...the AI not so much.\nThe FF is my least favorite among PC Sims.  With my T300 RS I used the Jack Spade files and after a lot of tweaking it is ok.  Cannot feel when the tires skid in straight line :(.  Graphically, awesome, content awesome.\nI hope for big fixes and a FF fix", "hours": 31.2, "user_id": "76561198357844263", "username": "Ryan Robbins", "products": 8, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "378860", "page": 6, "page_order": 7, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-06", "text": "Project Cars 2 is a massive improvement over the first title, this much is evident. If the PC series is the only sim series for you then stop reading here and buy Project Cars 2.\nEveryone else, people that want an exciting, enjoyable, realistic full sim or \"light\" sim (I hate the term Simcade) experience best look elsewhere.\nWhy? Project Cars 2 is dull. While the options on options for options and options on those will get any simmer salivating, that is it. The driving is where it matters and it just doesn't click here. I'm not one to go on and on about tyre friction and suspension and torque and yadadadada, I'm just going to say that it doesn't feel right. It just doesn't feel like other games such as Assetto Corsa, rFactor 2 and AMS do (and I'm not a massive fan of AMS).\nSome good points, decent car selection and variety, but some disciplines and groups are very lacking, offering only one or two vehicles. Tracks are good, probably the strongest point of the game. A decent selection of tracks with the \"classic\" Azure Coast from the original, but the rallycross is limited, the ovals are bland, as is the AI.\nThe worse element of this game for me, by far, is the sound design. It. Is. Awful. Nothing more immersion breaking than a monotonal NNNNRRRRRRRRRR while whizzing around the track. Whomever did the sound for PC2 must have had a cold at the time, or an ear infection.\nPC2 also loses out by any substantial modding support outside of car skins. For PC simming this is essential for longevity and versatility, which is why people play the likes of rFactor 1/2, Race07 etc even today. Functionally this is a console title, and as a PS4 owner myself I would think that this is reasonable, but with Assetto Corsa also on PS4, I would buy AC over it.\nSo, no, not for me. Project Cars 2 has the edge with a built in career mode, which for some is essential for that feel of progression. While rFactor 2 and Assetto Corsa lack these features stock, they each have mods that add a career progression to them, emulating a season of events with points, and even a iRacing like rating system for online racing. The built in career mode is not enough to win me over, sorry PC2.", "hours": 2.0, "user_id": "76561197996610226", "username": "lei07", "products": 628, "early_access": false}
