{"product_id": "609150", "page": 15, "page_order": 2, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-03", "text": "Anyone who dislike this game is probably having hardware issues and isnt always the games fault or cry babies about DRM if you hate DRM then get the \u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665 off steam. STEAM is a DRM\nNot only do you have waifu material it is an JRPG they're amazing, and will always be some of the top games I play next to Military Sims.\nStar Ocean is one of my favorite games and now its for PC!\nI wish I had more time to play like I did when I was little, but I'm pretty sure I will rack hours up little by little.", "hours": 4.5, "username": "Charioce", "products": 199, "early_access": false}
{"product_id": "609150", "page": 15, "page_order": 3, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-12-03", "text": "I bought this game with the intent of Let's Playing it. I own the original on the PS3 and have played it way more than any sane person should ever. I don't care about port quality; for my purposes it is ok and it functions as it should. If you want to read someone \u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665\u2665 about mouse support or why their ridiculous 96kHz audio setup is not supported, that is someone else. My chief-complaint in regards to porting is the lack of Playstation-type button prompts.\n\nLet me get this out of the way first: Improved graphics are nice. I get the impression that they desaturated the game a bit, which is a good thing, but, by far, the most impressive feature of this version of the game are the load times, which have been VASTLY improved, to the point of being basically non-existent. I'm sure they are there somewhere, but I have yet to actually notice a single loading screen.\nIt controls A LOT better than the PS3 version as well. It's still super clunky and awkward, but definitely better.\nAnd that's about all I can say for it. The story still sucks, the characters are still horrible, the art design in this thing is absolutely atrocious, both character and environment... What isn't overdone to hell and back is just as bland as the blandest thing there could possibly ever be. Gameplay is still interesting, but when stretched over 200+ hours of play time, there is no chance of it not being incredibly annoying. I like the fact that the character I choose to control actually affects how I play the game; tactics and such. You can overlevel and button mash it, but there is at least a genuine attempt at depth. Gameplay wise, it is an interesting game with nice ideas, but there is just SO MUCH working against it.\nYou can clear the game in about 50-80 hours. For reference, speed running it takes around 3 hours. Getting all the achievements is a 400 hours investment. Minimum. So if you are keen to your 100%'s, either come prepared or skip this one.\nThis is a game you can play and kind of enjoy. There is some good stuff to laugh at and there are some genuine moments of thrill and brilliance in the battle system. The bosses feel a bit cheap at times but mostly it works well enough and provide decent challenge.\nI feel like I should mention that Star Ocean requires a rather high tolerance for anime tropes; anime tropes done poorly and rather straight-faced, by the way. In the end, I do think that there is A LOT to really, passionately HATE about this game. But for some bizarre and inexplicable reason, I keep coming back to it. Everything in my heart says that I should never ever recommend this game, but I do think it's worth a shot, specially if you come in with an open mind about how much of a sh*tfest it is actually going to be. Sometimes you just have to take the bad with the good... Or the absolutely awful with the kinda OK, in this case.\n...\nStockholm Syndrome / 10, basically.", "hours": 90.9, "username": "Ivan Osorio", "products": 287, "found_funny": 15, "early_access": false}
