{"product_id": "378860", "page": 8, "page_order": 9, "recommended": true, "date": "2018-01-02", "text": "To put it short, I really do recommend this game. The amount of possibilities within this game are fantastic, from a classic Rallycross race around DirtFish using old Ford Escorts to a modern WEC Endurance race fighting LMP1 cars and GTE cars against one another around the Le Mans circuit for hours.\nPros:\nTracks: Fantastic amount of tracks and variation, with a good mix of long tracks, short, road circuits, sprint races and rallycross tracks. There's also variations of each track so you get more choice on what route of the track you wish to race on. There's also historic versions of tracks such of Spa and Monza which I found a great addition to the game.\nCars: Lots of cars, especially for those that love race cars. With numerous amounts of cars from classes such as GT3, GT4, LMP1, WRX, Group A, Touring Cars, Indycar and so on. There's bound to be a vehicle for you. There's also a handful of road cars to use, though these could do with some additions. There's also track day cars such as the McLaren P1 GTR and Aston Martin Vulcan, which may I add sounds absolutely phenomenal, which brings me to my next point.\nSounds: The sounds within the game are just superb. As previously stated, the Aston Martin Vulcan sounds fantastic, hearing that mighty V12 engine fly past you is a sound to hear. And the variation in the sound of each car is great and shows that SMS didn't cut corners and use the same sounds for multiple cars. Also, just as a personal point, the WRX are some of the nicest sounding cars I've ever heard. Sliding round corners with the Honda Civic WRX, listening to the engine roaring and the backfire is truly something.\nGraphics: Project CARS 1 was praised for its photo realistic graphics, and this sequel is no different in the quality it gives. Unlike games such as Forza and GT Sport which go for more eye candy than photo realistic, Project CARS 2 may not look as nice as the other two, but it looks the most photo realistic.\nWeather: The weather within this game is next level. With the introduction of Live Track 3.0, SMS rwally upped their game with this. The fact you can start a race in clear dry conditions, to then advance to a thunder storm, where puddles form around the lower sections of track, surfaces become slippery and then go to an overcast evening, giving time for some of the puddles to dry up and the cars to dry the track as they continue to race and then for it to become night time and a blizzard cones along, removing the view of the drivers and really giving them a hard time, forming puddles around the track and making the experience something new. This is what I had in one of my first races on this game at Le Mans in a 2 hour race in a Nissan GTR GT3 (it was a custom race, of course).\nPhysics: The most important part of this game, the physics. Though not perfect, they are pretty good, especially for the race cars such as the GT3 or Formula A. It has massively improved over the last game, as you can now drift vehicles properly, you can stop your car from completely spinning out and so on. It also works very well with a controller this time, as I put my first 50 hours into this game using a knock off Xbox 360 controller and really enjoyed it. With wheel, well, it's obviously even more fun. The rallycross cars feel fantastic in this game with a wheel, and are definitely some of the most fun cars to drive in this game.\nNow, the cons:\nTracks: Not too much for the tracks, other than the game could do with more road races like the California Highway, as this is certainly one of the more fun tracks, and road tracks are lacking greatly in this game, as well as spring tracks such as California Highway.\nCars: Could definitely do with more road cars, as these are very low in number, especially within the lower classes. The game could also do better off with more liveries for some cars such as the Bentley, more solid colours for car such as the Ford Raptor, more custom livery spots for vehicles and a way to download custom liveties in game through some kind of workshop.\nGraphics: My main dislike with the graphics is the snow, as I don't think it looks very good, especially once it has landed on cars. I also get a bug quite often where the grass starts floating in the air which can be quite annoying.\nWeather: Can't say there's much wrong with it, as it's all very good. More types of weather would always be fun, such as hail, strong winds, heat waves and so on.\nPhysics: these could definitely be better, especially for the road cars, as I often find some of these very difficult to drive. Cars such as Renault Clio TC1 is very odo to drive, as I find it seems to slide a lot and in some cases tips over.\nOverall, I think this is one amazing game, and couldn't recommend it more to anyone that's looking to get into some simple racing or is a car/motorsport enthusiast.", "hours": 109.9, "username": "Sono", "products": 200, "early_access": false}
