{"product_id": "661360", "page": 1, "page_order": 0, "recommended": true, "date": "2017-11-22", "text": "This is a really good game.\nYou have to complete your bug-free game by release day which requires fixing some buggy code packages. Every \"package\" (i.e. stage) contains several \"files\" (i.e. levels) that have bugs which must be found and fixed. You need to avoid obstacles like enemies and spikes along the way, as well as surviving against the package's glitches. Each package has a set of glitches across all the files which change characteristics of the world (such as enemy size doubling or low gravity). As well as finding the bug in each level, there are also secondary objectives to be found that let you play a fun mini-game for a chance to permanently remove a glitch from the package to make those levels a bit easier. There's also glitches that you can find along the way to collect and use for yourself as a special move to help beat the level (such as jetpacks or inverting gravity). If you have a tough time or don't like the glitches for a particular package, you can refactor it which re-assigns a new random set of glitches to the package at the cost of losing deadline time.\nI've been having a lot of fun with it. The gradual build-up of difficulty on each package feels great and gets fairly challenging toward the last one. The inventive gameplay feels very well balanced in many ways and makes you want to immediately keep trying again after death. The game has a very unique feel to it with well-designed graphics and sound. I didn't experience any technical issues and the user interface is solid too. If I had to choose, it kind of reminds me of a hybrid of Pony Island, Rogue Legacy, Broforce, and Super Meat Boy. The only thing that I could see some people not liking is the character's jumping/movement which is very quick/fluid and tends to overshoot easily such as in Super Meat Boy.\nDefinitely worth the price!", "hours": 4.1, "username": "fantomchoder", "products": 523, "early_access": false}
